      content: `Park,  Wednesday Night, May 6, Drayton Hall, Charleston, SC (Chamber of Commerce Gala)


When I see her, I’m nursing a whiskey at our round banquet table, half-listening to Kidman and Matthew argue about our latest case. A flash of electric-red satin at the hall’s entrance. Who…? My thoughts stall out.

Everything around me dulls to static. The laughter of my colleagues, the clinking of silverware, and the jazz music all fade as my eyes track the woman in the red gown. She’s tall, poised, gliding through the crowd like she owns the place. The dress hugs her figure in all the right ways, shimmering under the chandeliers. God, she’s gorgeous. I don’t realize I’ve practically twisted around in my chair until she passes our table and I catch a glimpse of her from behind. The sway of her hips sends a hot jolt straight through me. I swallow hard.

A sudden BANG on the table jolts me so hard I nearly drop my glass. I blink, torn from my trance. Detective Matthew Anderson, seated to my left, has slammed his fist on the table. He’s smirking. On my right, my wife is staring daggers at me. Slowly, the world rushes back into focus, along with the realization that I’ve been completely oblivious about my ogling.

My face heats. A few of the guys around the table snicker. I attempt a casual sip of my drink, but Caroline’s scowl could turn me to stone.

“You’ve, uh, got some soup on your chin, man,” says Attorney Kidman, hiding a grin.

I wipe my mouth quickly. “Where? Did I—?”

Kidman bursts out laughing. “Oh, my bad. Not soup. Just your drool.”

The whole table cracks up at my expense. Everyone except Caroline. She’s gone stiff and silent, which is even worse than her glares. Damn it, Park, get it together.

At the table, we have a motley crew: Detective Matthew, my oldest friend, his wife Angela, Kidman, my junior partner from work, and his latest date for the week. And then my sweet wife, Caroline, and I. A cozy little group for what was supposed to be a professional networking event. Instead, I’ve turned it into a circus by gawking at a pretty stranger. I duck my head, trying to laugh along with the jokes about me, but my neck burns with shame. Caroline’s going to eviscerate me the first chance she gets, that much is certain.

Mercifully, Matthew decides to throw me a lifeline and steer the conversation back to something less mortifying. He clears his throat. “Anyway, about the Aaron Mitchell case…” Matthew fixes me with a sympathetic but firm look. “It’s over, Park. I’m telling you, you’re not going to win this one. Not with your client.”

I exhale, grateful for the subject change, and latch on. “C’mon, have a little faith in me.”

Matthew shakes his head, swirling the ice in his bourbon. “My buddies in the DA’s office say the prosecution’s coming out swinging. They want Mitchell’s head on a spike. You can have all the courtroom swagger in the world, but it won’t matter. The evidence is rock solid against him.”

Kidman, never one to back down, scoffs at that. “We’ll be swinging just as hard, trust me. Besides, the Mitchell family’s paying a fortune for defense. And if we pull off an acquittal, the firm’s name goes through the roof.” He winks at me. “Untouchable Crown Prince of Charleston Courtrooms, isn’t that what they call you?”

A few chuckles. Caroline pointedly rolls her eyes, still arms-crossed and fuming. I can practically hear her thoughts: Men and their egos.

Matthew isn’t convinced. “I’d give you one in a billion odds, my friend. The guy bludgeoned his wife’s skull in with a sledgehammer. For Christ’s sake, even you must have a hard time defending that.”

Kidman bristles. “Allegedly. Allegedly bludgeoned. How about we let the jury decide, huh? Or are we skipping trials nowadays and just lynching people?”

I zone out as they bicker, my attention sliding back toward the entrance of the ballroom. I scan for that red dress… there. She’s across the hall now, and my stomach does a weird flip when I see who she’s sitting with. The District Attorney’s table. Of course, she just had to be in the enemy’s camp. She throws her head back in a laugh at something a portly older man says. 

DA Jerry Sullivan, I recognize him even from here. The sight of her laughing with Jerry’s crew sends an irrational stab of disappointment.

Why is she with them? I wonder. She doesn’t look like a typical Charleston prosecutor. Those types are usually more pedestrian in fashion. Maybe she’s a visiting dignitary for the gala, or a new hire? If she were local, I’d remember that face.

As I’m musing, a sharp, shrill voice right beside me almost makes me jump.

“Oh, for God’s sake! My dress is ruined!” Caroline’s voice is loud enough to turn heads at nearby tables and cuts through the din.

I whip around to see her staring down in horror at a spreading dark red stain on her teal silk gown. The smell of cabernet wafts up, and her wine glass is toppled on the white tablecloth. She must have knocked it over.

Instinctively, I reach for a napkin. “It’s not that bad, love. Just dab it, maybe in the bathroom—”

Caroline rounds on me with fiery eyes. “This dress costs thousands, Park! You can’t just scrub it with some bargain-bin detergent. It’ll ruin the fabric!” She grabs a handful of napkins anyway, blotting furiously as her voice rises. “Ugh, it’s spreading…Jesus, I look like a disaster!”

A bead of sweat threatens her perfectly made-up face. Around the table, everyone pointedly looks away, giving us a semblance of privacy as Caroline panics. Well, everyone except Angela, who reaches over kindly: “Why not run home and change?” She suggests. “We’re not far. You could be back in half an hour.”

I close my eyes for a split second, knowing exactly what’s coming. Caroline latches onto Angela’s idea like a lifeline. She’s painfully self-conscious about impressions. And tonight we’re supposed to meet Chief Justice Roberts, the guest of honor. A wine-stained gown simply will not do in Caroline’s mind.

“Yes!” Caroline gasps, already pushing her chair back. “Park, take me home right now. I’ll change and we’ll come straight back.”

Her tone allows no argument. And truly, any protest I could make would only prolong this scene, which I desperately want to end. I force what I hope passes for a calm smile. “Fine. Let’s make it quick, then.”

Under the table, I clench my jaw. There goes our night. Caroline always wins, period. I scramble to gather my phone and wallet as she’s already standing. As I rise, I can’t help one last furtive glance across the hall, just to see the woman in red again. One more look, that’s all. My gaze finds her table. She’s listening to someone, her profile to me…

A hard stare bores into the side of my face. I don’t need peripheral vision to know it’s Caroline, catching me in the act yet again. My neck prickles. I straighten up and avoid eye contact with my wife as I murmur a goodbye to the group. 

Great, another strike against me for the drive home.

We weave through the round tables toward the exit. I place a hand at the small of Caroline’s back, but she pointedly steps a little faster, my hand slipping off. The moment we escape the ballroom into the quieter marble foyer, I exhale. “We’ll be back before dessert,” I say lamely, trying to cut the tension.

She just presses her lips thin and marches toward the coat check.

We’re almost to the front doors of Drayton Hall when a brash, nasal voice echoes from behind us: “Park Limond! Defender of degenerates and murderers, from the noble House of Fleck & Garrison!”

I cringe. That voice is unmistakable. Caroline huffs an annoyed breath and steps aside; she already knows what’s coming.

Plastering on a tight smile, I turn to face Jerry Sullivan, Charleston’s District Attorney and my long-time courtroom nemesis. He’s hurrying toward us, tuxedo strained around his middle. A few onlookers pause their conversations to watch; Jerry has always loved an audience.

“Good evening, Sullivan,” I say smoothly. “Or should I say Sullen-man? You look…wider these days. All those big cases you’ve lost must be converting to body mass, huh?” I give his gut a pointed once-over.

A chorus of “ooh” from a few folks nearby scores one for me. Jerry’s round face goes ruddy. “Hilarious. Keep laughing while you can, Limond. Because in a few weeks, I’ll enjoy watching my team crush you in court.”

He pokes a stubby finger at my chest. I casually bat his hand aside. “Your baby lawyers are cute, Jerry. But you lots haven’t given me a good fight in years. Even for me, it’s kinda boring winning every damn time.”

Jerry sneers. Seemingly struggling for a clap back. 

A muscle in my jaw twitches. Jerry and I have tangled in courtrooms more times than I can count, and I’ve beaten him way more than he would have liked. And for that, he hates me. But he might have a winning chance this time, as I really don’t have much to work with in Mitchell’s defense. Still, I won’t give him the satisfaction of acknowledging that.

“By the way, Limond. You might not even be facing me in court. I’ve got a new hotshot on my team. I’m thinking of letting her handle you instead.”

Her. My mind jumps immediately to the woman in the red dress. Could it be…?

Knowing how impatient Caroline can be, I raise my hands in a mock placating gesture. “Why don’t we save the trash talk for Monday’s trial, eh? Wouldn’t want to bore all these fine people with our bromance.” I can’t resist the slight jab.


Jerry’s grin tells me everything. He snorts. “ADA Bridgette Leah. Just transferred from New York last month. She’s smarter than she looks, so don’t let that model face fool you. Watching her wipe the floor with you in court will probably be the highlight of my year.”

I open my mouth, but before I can respond, Caroline’s voice, icy cold, slices in: “How much longer is this little chat going to last? Or should I leave you two alone?” She has rejoined us, arms crossed and foot tapping. The temperature in her stare could freeze molten lava.

Jerry has the gall to smirk. “Don’t worry, Mrs. Limond, I’m done with him. For now.” He gives her a polite nod. “Always a pleasure.”

Caroline forces a tight smile. “Likewise,” she hisses afterward. 

I manage a quick farewell handshake with Jerry. Then I gently touch Caroline’s elbow to guide her out the grand double doors. She doesn’t shake me off this time, but her silence is thunderous. 

Only when we’re safely in the valet-parked Mercedes and pulling away from Drayton Hall does Caroline break the silence. And when she does, it’s with a single seething word: “Unbelievable!”`
