      content: `Caroline,  Wednesday Night, May 6, En route from Drayton Hall


He doesn’t even have the spine to say a word. The whole drive, Park keeps his eyes fixed on the road, hands at ten-and-two, jaw clenched. The silence in the car is suffocating, broken only by the soft whoosh of Charleston’s streetlights passing by and the low hum of the engine.

My blood is boiling. Every time I replay that scene at the gala, Park practically drooling over that woman while I sat right there, fresh humiliation washes over me. And those snickering fools at our table, seeing me publicly disrespected? God. I dig my nails into my palms to quell the rage.

Finally, I can’t stand it. I break the silence. “So. You’ve got nothing to say?” I spit out. My voice trembles with contained venom.

Park flinches almost imperceptibly. “Caroline—” he begins, eyes still on the road.

“Don’t you Caroline me.” I’m just getting started. “You embarrassed me back there, Park. In front of our friends. In front of half the damn city elite!” My voice rises with each sentence. I’ve been holding this in since the ballroom, and it’s erupting now, unstoppable.

He opens his mouth, then closes it. Keeps driving. That infuriating silence again.

“Oh, what, you’re not going to say anything?” I challenge. “Nothing at all? Not even an apology? Or at least a pathetic excuse?”

He swallows. I can see his grip tighten on the steering wheel. “I—”

“You know what I think?” I cut him off, words laced with acid. “I think this is because I didn’t give you sex last week. Is your horny meter already in the red? One week of self-control too much for you, darling?” The sarcasm drips heavily on that last word.

Park’s cheeks darken. “That’s not—”

“Not what? Not true? Could’ve fooled me, with how you ogled that cheap slut at the table.” I glare at him. He’s still not looking at me, which only fuels my anger. “You couldn’t keep it in your pants even during a professional dinner? Right beside your wife?”

He finally speaks, voice low. “I’m sorry. I screwed up. She…caught my eye for a second, and the fool in me lost control. I didn’t—”

“A second?!” I bark out a harsh laugh. “You stared at her like a starving dog eyes a steak. For minutes, Park. Minutes while I sat right there.” My chest heaves; I realize I’m breathing hard, adrenaline lighting up my limbs. This is pure, raw anger. But beneath it, an ache of hurt. I push that hurt down, channeling it into fury, because fury is power.

He risks a glance at me. “You’re right. I was wrong. I was an asshole. I have no excuse.” His voice is trembling slightly. Good, he should be afraid.

I glare at him, waiting. That can’t be all. Does he think a meek admission fixes this?

When I don’t respond, Park stammers on, “I… I’m truly sorry, Caroline. I don’t know what came over me. I just—”

“Enough.” My voice comes out icy, belying the storm inside me. I turn to stare out my window at the blur of streetlights. An apology means nothing right now. The humiliation was public; a mumble in the car isn’t going to erase that image from everyone’s mind.

From the corner of my eye, I see Park’s shoulders sag a little. But I’m nowhere near ready to forgive or let this go. Frankly, I’m close to exploding again.

The light ahead turns red. Park slows the car to a stop at the deserted intersection. I can feel him mustering the courage to speak again. But I won’t give him the chance.

My right foot shoots out and stomps on Park’s foot over the brake pedal. Hard.

The Mercedes screeches violently to a halt. Tires squeal, the car fishtailing just a foot before the white stop line. I hear a distant horn. A truck behind us, maybe? And for a fraction of a second, my heart hammers with the realization that could have been dangerous.

Park slams his foot on the brake and yells, “Jesus Christ! Caroline!” He’s braced against the wheel, eyes wide as he looks at me like I’ve lost my mind. “Are you insane? You could’ve gotten us killed if that truck ran into us!”

I meet his shocked gaze with a cold smile. My pulse is racing, but I force steady words. “Oh, so you needed a near-death experience to find your voice? Interesting.”

He’s breathing hard. “What the hell was that for?!”

“What was it for?” I echo incredulously. “Why’d I do that? Hmm, maybe because I’m furious, Park. Because you sitting there like a mute wasn’t satisfying me.” I lean toward him, my anger rekindled to white-hot. “Don’t you dare ever ignore me like that again.”

He rubs a hand over his face, trying to compose himself. The light turns green, and a car behind us honks. Park quickly steers us to the side of the road and puts the car in park, hazard lights blinking.

The moment we’re off the road, I continue, voice deadly quiet now. “Why did you humiliate me like that tonight? Staring at some tramp while I’m sitting right next to you. Do you have any idea how that made me look? How it made me feel?”

His expression crumples. “I know, I know. I messed up. Caroline, I am so sorry.” He reaches a hand toward me hesitantly, as if to touch my arm. I pull away.

“A public apology back at that table would’ve been better,” I snap. “Instead of this private groveling when no one can hear you.”

Pain flickers in his eyes, good. I want it to hurt. I want him to remember this pain the next time he even thinks of eyeing another woman.

I take a deep breath. Enough. I’ve yelled, he’s apologized. I’ve made my point. And truth be told, the rush of adrenaline is ebbing, leaving me a bit shaken at my own outburst. I glance out the windshield. We’re only a few blocks from home now. My heart is still hammering, and not just from rage. There was a split second I genuinely thought we might crash. The realization makes me swallow hard. I could have hurt myself, too, not just him.

Park is watching me warily. He seems at a loss for words now. His face is lined with regret, and something about that deflates some of my anger. He truly does look sorry.

I sigh and lean back in my seat, suddenly exhausted. “Just…drive.”

He silently puts the car back in gear and merges onto the road. We complete the last few minutes to our house in an uneasy silence, with not even the radio on.

When we pull into the driveway of our home, a modern duplex in the prestigious Rainbow Row district, I have my mask of calm back on. The Limond house. Once upon a time, it was the home of Park, his first wife, and their three sons, a lively family of five. Now it’s just Park and me.

As I step through the front door, the foyer light automatically comes on, illuminating the tasteful decor I spent so much time perfecting. But my mind isn’t on the furnishings. It’s on ghosts, the ghosts of those early days when I used to come here just as the babysitter for Park’s kids, before any of this seemed possible. The kids: Park Jr., Harry, and little Josh, were absolute hellraisers back then. And later, as adults, even worse. At least they’re out of the picture now.

I realize I’ve murmured that out loud: “At least they’re history now.”

“What’s that?” Park asks quietly from behind me, setting down his keys.

I plaster on a quick smile and turn to him. “Oh, nothing. Just…thinking about a difficult client session I had years ago. Glad those days are behind me.” I wave a hand as if to dismiss it, then pivot to head upstairs. “I’m going to change. Check on me in twenty minutes, will you?” My voice is suddenly sweet, almost tender.

Park looks a little surprised at my tone. Perhaps he expected me to continue raging. But I’ve decided to take a different tack tonight. I gave him the tongue-lashing; now it’s time for something different.

He nods, relief evident in his eyes that I seem calmer. “Sure. Twenty minutes.”

I leave him and hurry up the curved staircase toward the master bedroom. The moment I’m alone in our room, I shut the door and let out a shaky breath. My reflection in the vanity mirror catches my eye: Caroline, get a hold of yourself.

My cheeks are flushed, eyes a bit wild. God, I haven’t been that angry in a long time. There’s a tiny tremble in my fingers as I reach back to unzip my ruined gown.

The teal fabric slips off, revealing my naked body beneath. I walk to the full-length mirror on the wall. The sight that greets me would normally boost my confidence instantly: an hourglass figure, flawless skin with a golden glow, full breasts sitting high and firm, thanks to Dr. Holmes’s masterful work last summer. At nearly 40, I can still turn heads, and I’ve paid good money and put in serious effort to ensure that. I run my hands down my waist and hips. 

I have the body of a goddess. 

So what the hell else does he want? A Barbie doll with a tinier waist or wider hips? Or is it just the novelty of someone new? My lip curls in disgust as I imagine that red-dress bimbo naked. I bet she’s rail-thin, one of those lanky model types. Totally not Park’s usual type as he’s typically into curves, but I guess the thrill of new flesh is universal.

I feel a pang of something unpleasant, jealousy, yes, but also a deeper kind of fear, and I hate it. This insecurity is not me. I’m Caroline Foster Limond: smart, successful (in my own way), and a damn catch. I straighten my spine, meeting my own gaze in the mirror. He chose me, didn’t he? Out of all the women throwing themselves at him, he married me. He left Aiyana and their kids for me! So, I can’t let some pretty newcomer rattle my confidence.

A knock at the door pulls me from my thoughts. Park’s voice, tentative: “Can I come in now?”

I panic-flinch. “Not yet! Five more minutes,” I call, scrambling to grab a dress from my walk-in closet.

I pick the first thing that my hand touches, a plum-purple cocktail dress with cap sleeves. It’s not nearly as glamorous as the teal gown, but it’s decent enough. I slip it on and quickly smooth my hair. My makeup needs a touch-up. I notice my mascara is smudged from when I rubbed my eyes in frustration earlier. Damn it.

Another knock, louder this time. Ugh, he’s persistent. Well, better to let him in now that I’m dressed; I need him for phase two.

“Yeah, come in,” I say, moving to perch on the edge of the bed. I arrange myself to look a bit pitiful, one hand on my stomach, face tilted down.

Park enters fast, worry all over his face. “Kidman just texted,” he blurts, still catching his breath. “Chief Justice Roberts arrived… apparently he was looking for me. We’re running late, Caroline. We need to go if we’re—”

I don’t move. Instead, I close my eyes and press my palm harder against my belly. “Honey…I—I don’t feel so good.” I make my voice small, pained. “I think I have food poisoning. It’s probably that damn salad from earlier.”

Park freezes a foot from me. Instantly, the urgent annoyance about being late evaporates from his expression, replaced by concern. “Is it bad? What hurts?”

I let out a low groan for effect, curling slightly on the bed. In truth, I feel perfectly fine physically, but he doesn’t need to know that. “My stomach… it really hurts.”

I can see the transformation in him: from frustrated husband to panicked caregiver in about two seconds. He steps closer, worry creasing his brow. “Caroline, love… okay, okay. Let’s get you to the clinic.”

Before I can even protest, he scoops me up in his arms. I make a little squeak, half genuine surprise, half acting, as he lifts me. “No, I can walk.” I mumble.

“It’s faster like this,” he insists, already carrying me out of the bedroom. “If it’s your ulcer flaring up or something, we’re not taking chances.”

He’s moving so quickly. I loop my arms around his neck, leaning against his chest. I can feel his heart pounding. Is he…scared? For me? The thought causes an unexpected twinge of guilt. But only a twinge.

He practically flies down the stairs with me and out to the car. Gently, he sets me in the passenger seat. I make sure to wince and cradle my abdomen as he buckles me in. His hands are slightly shaky.

“I’ll get you right to St. Francis, hang on.” There’s a tremor in his voice too.

He dashes back inside briefly. He likely forgot his wallet or keys. The moment he’s gone, I drop the act. A satisfied smile creeps onto my face. Hook. Line. Sinker. As expected, Park fell for it entirely. The perfect escape from the gala, and now I have his full attention and sympathy.

He returns, and we speed off toward the clinic. Park, the ever rule-abiding lawyer, actually blows through two stop signs and exceeds the speed limit the whole way. I hear a honk at one intersection as he aggressively overtakes a slow driver. He doesn’t even swear at them like he normally might; instead, all his focus is on me, one hand clutching mine, the other on the wheel.

I almost want to laugh at how easy this is, but I keep my face drawn in discomfort, eyes closed. Inside, I’m brimming with a dark glee. Now he knows how it feels to be humiliated and powerless. I imagine how it must burn him that he missed reuniting with his hero, Justice Roberts. An opportunity that might never come again. The sting of that disappointment will stick with Park for a long time. Good.

We arrive at St. Francis Specialist Clinic, and Park rushes me in through the sliding ER doors. The next hour is a blur of playing the ill damsel. Park works his charm on the triage nurse to get me seen quickly. I watch through half-lidded eyes as he flashes his winning smile and maybe a hint of a bribe. Within minutes, I’m in a private exam room with a doctor.

“Can I speak to you alone?” I ask the doctor sweetly after introductions. Park looks reluctant to leave my side, but the doctor gently ushers him out.

The moment we’re alone, I drop the feeble act and calmly explain to the young doctor that I suspect a minor ulcer flare-up and perhaps an adverse reaction to some painkillers I took earlier, all fake, of course.. I just need them to keep me overnight for observation and some fluids. The doctor buys it, ordering tests that I know will show nothing major.

When Park comes back in, the doctor assures him it’s likely just an ulcer flare and that I’ll be fine after some observation.. Park visibly deflates in relief, thanking the doctor profusely. I even catch him giving the doctor’s arm a grateful pat. And the doctor, who can’t be more than thirty and looks mildly starstruck by Park’s attention, blushes.

Hours later, I’m settled in a comfy hospital bed, propped up slightly, with an IV drip and everything. Park sits by my side, tension lining his face as he checks his phone repeatedly. It’s almost midnight. He must have texted Kidman updates, because he’s not getting peppered with messages anymore.

I let my eyes stay closed, feigning half-sleep, and murmur, “What’s wrong, honey? Something more important than me?”

He hesitates. “Not really. It’s just…Kidman keeps texting. Apparently Chief Justice Roberts did ask about me. I missed the chance to chat with him.” His tone is regretful, almost childishly disappointed. “But— but I can’t leave you here alone. So.”

I bite back a smirk. Classic Park, even now, is trying to guilt-trip me in his way. Well, he can stew in that missed opportunity. I certainly don’t intend to encourage him to go back. Instead, I keep my eyes closed and just sigh as if in pain.

He squeezes my hand. “There’s always next time, I guess,” he says softly, though I can hear the bitterness. “Maybe Roberts will visit Charleston again… or not. It’s been years since he last did.”

A tiny, satisfied smile threatens my lips, but I don’t let it show. In my chest, I feel a warm glow of victory. My message was received loud and clear: Park had to choose between networking with a powerful figure and taking care of his wife, and he chose me. As he damn well should.

Eventually, exhaustion from the emotional rollercoaster catches up to me. The nurses gave me a mild sedative ‘to help with pain’ and it’s making my eyelids heavy for real. Park is still sitting vigil, the poor, loyal husband. Perhaps he’s hoping this display of devotion will earn my forgiveness by morning.

Before I drift off, I allow myself one last smug thought: Mission accomplished.`
