      content: `Park,  Thursday, May 7, Sheriff Al Cannon Detention Center, Charleston


I rub my bleary eyes and gulp the last of a large black coffee as I push through the heavy doors of the detention center. The sterile scent of disinfectant and the dull buzz of fluorescents greet me, along with a stern-looking deputy behind the check-in desk.

Running on maybe two hours of sleep, courtesy of the overnight hospital stay with Caroline, I feel like a zombie wearing a suit. But I can’t reschedule this morning’s task. This is my first in-person meeting with the infamous Aaron Mitchell, and I need every scrap of intel I can get if I’m going to defend him.

Kidman is already here, pacing the small waiting area like an anxious caged animal. The moment he sees me, he checks his watch with exaggerated indignation. “You said eight o’clock, boss. It’s half past. Is this your version of eight?” he snaps, keeping his voice low but heated. “I’ve been here forever. These deputies keep eyeing me like they’re about to lock me up too.”

I suppress a groan. Right. I did tell him 8:00 am sharp. “Sorry, Kid. Had…a situation last night.” I can’t exactly go into detail here, so I hesitate over the choice of my next words. 

Kidman scowls. “Everything okay?”

“Fine,” I say. “Caroline’s fine. It was nothing.” I jerk my head toward the reception desk. “Did you check us in?”

“Yes, yes. They’re grabbing Mitchell from his cell.” He blows out a breath. “These guards have been staring me down since I got here. You know they hate us defense lawyers.”

I muster a weak smirk. “Maybe because you introduced yourself the moment you walked in? I told you, just sit quietly and wait. Nothing riles up these law-and-order types like knowing we’re from Fleck & Garrison. In their eyes, we’re just money-hungry sharks getting rich by keeping scum on the streets.”

Kidman smirks back. “They’re not entirely wrong.”

I let out a tired chuckle. He’s not wrong either. But hey, I didn’t design the system. I just excel at playing it.

We approach the reception counter to sign in formally. The deputy, a broad-shouldered man with a military haircut, barely looks at us, stone-faced. Beside him, a second officer, a woman with kind eyes, gives a polite smile.

“Morning, Mrs. Wendy,” I say, reading her name tag and turning on the charm despite my fatigue.

Her eyes flicker in recognition. “Good morning, Mister. Welcome.”

The male deputy’s scowl deepens. I catch the name “Carver” on his badge; I ignore him and keep my focus on Wendy. “It’s Mrs., right? I recall from last time… You could pass for a college freshman though, even in uniform.” I give her an easy grin.

A slight pink rises in her cheeks. “Oh— well. It’s Mrs., yes. And thank you.” Her smile falters for a second, probably remembering she’s supposed to be professional. “Um, if you’ll both sign here… Mr. Mitchell will be brought to Interview Room B shortly.”

We sign in. Deputy Carver mutters something under his breath as he picks up the phone to notify someone of our arrival. I ignore the side commentary; Wendy’s handling us now, and that’s enough.

Within a few minutes, a door buzzes open down the hall, and a corrections officer leads a man in an orange jumpsuit toward us. I square my shoulders, trying to push aside personal prejudices. 

Time to meet the devil.

Aaron Mitchell, late 50s, looks… surprisingly ordinary, given his reputation. He’s of medium height, a bit paunchy, with thinning gray hair. If I passed him on the street, I’d think he was a math teacher or someone’s grandpa. It’s the eyes that give pause: something steely and cold in them, even as he sizes me up with a polite smile.

“Mr. Mitchell, I’m Park Limond, your attorney,” I say, extending a hand.

He gives me a firm handshake. His palms are calloused. “Good to meet you, Mr. Limond. Heard a lot about you.” His voice is gravelly, with a hint of Southern twang.

“All good things, I hope.” I motioned for him to follow me into the private meeting room. Kidman trails us, shutting the door behind.

We all sit at a plain metal table. The guard waits outside, but I know we’re likely being observed through the small window, and our conversation may be recorded if we’re not careful. Attorney-client confidentiality means nothing to some of these folks, unfortunately. I lean forward and speak in a measured tone.

“Alright, Aaron. We don’t have much time, so I’ll get straight to it. The prosecution’s case against you is strong. I need you to be completely honest with me if I’m going to help you. Understood?”

His jaw tightens a fraction. “I understand.”

We start going over his version of events. It’s a grim story: his wife, Marjorie, was found bludgeoned to death in their garage with his sledgehammer lying beside her. No witnesses, but plenty of circumstantial evidence pointing to him: a history of domestic disputes, his fingerprints on the weapon, and strange inconsistencies in his alibi.

He swears up and down he didn’t do it. “I loved Marjorie,” he says fervently, leaning forward. “We had our fights, but I’d never… I couldn’t…” His eyes actually misted a little. It’s either genuine or an Oscar-worthy performance. Hard to tell.

As he talks, I notice something interesting whenever he denies guilt: a slight twitch in his left eye. Hmm.

Kidman starts asking details about the timeline, and Aaron answers, but something in my gut twists. He’s lying. Or at least hiding something. I’ve interviewed enough clients to sense when bits don’t add up. He’s adamant he was at home watching TV when Marjorie was killed, but he hesitated slightly when I asked what he was watching. He eventually said Wheel of Fortune, which doesn’t even air at the time he gave.

After an hour, we’ve covered most of the ground. My notepad is filled with scribbles, a lot of them question marks. We’ll need to corroborate whatever parts of his story we can. Right now, it’s looking bleak.

I decide to confront him a bit, see if I can shake something loose. “Aaron, the evidence suggests Marjorie was trying to leave you. Neighbors heard her say she was moving out just the day before she died. If that’s true, it gives you a motive , anger, abandonment, etc. What do you say to that?”

He clasps his hands, eyes downcast. “She… she talked about leaving sometimes, but she never meant it. Couples fight, you know.”

My gaze stays on him, unblinking. “The neighbors say you had a screaming match that day. That she wanted a divorce and you told her ‘Over my dead body.’ ”

His nostrils flare. “I never said that. People love to gossip and embellish. I won’t deny we fought. But I’d have never hurt her.”

The eye twitched again. A memory of something flickers behind his eyes, I swear.

Kidman jumps in, seeing my line of questioning might be hitting a nerve. “Look, if there’s anything… anything you’re keeping from us, now’s the time, Aaron. We can’t defend what we don’t know. And the DA will crawl up every orifice of your life to find surprises, so spare us those surprises.”

Aaron’s face hardens. “I’m telling you everything I know. I didn’t kill my wife. Find the bastard who did, instead of grilling me.”

I lean back, exchanging a glance with Kidman. Mitchell’s getting defensive and angry. So, probably not useful to push harder right now. We’ll have to investigate alternate suspects on our own. The truth is likely somewhere in the middle: maybe he didn’t plan to kill her, but a fight escalated and… No. I can’t think like that. If I believe he’s guilty, I can’t defend him properly.

Right. Time to find an alternative theory to cling to.

I force a reassuring smile. “Alright. We hear you. Our job is to defend you, and we will. But you’ve got to help us by thinking: who else could have done this? Do you have any enemies? Was Marjorie involved with anyone, any affair, or someone with a grudge?”

He shakes his head emphatically. “No affairs. She wasn’t like that. Enemies… none that I know of. I mean, my older son from a previous marriage, he never got along with Marjorie, but he wouldn’t…”

He trails off. My ears perk up. “Your son? What’s his name?”

“Derek. But he lives in Tennessee and he and Marjorie haven’t spoken in years. I only mentioned it because of the word ‘enemies.’ Derek’s not an enemy, he just… disapproved of her.” Aaron frowns, seemingly realizing he might have given us a lead inadvertently. “But Derek’s a good boy. He wouldn’t hurt anyone. And he wasn’t even around.”

I take note of that. Kidman, ever pragmatic, asks, “Do you have life insurance on Marjorie?”

Aaron bristles, insulted. “Yeah, a policy. But nothing huge. I didn’t kill her for insurance money, if that’s what you’re implying.”

I file away Kidman’s question. It’s a fair angle: follow the money. Something to check out later.

We wrap up the meeting with a few more minor clarifications. As the guard comes to take Aaron back, I stand and grip his shoulder lightly. “We’re going to do everything we can, Aaron. I know it’s tough, but hang in there. And remember, if anyone inside tries to get you to talk about the case, don’t. Only speak freely to me or our investigator.”

He nods, some of that earlier aggression gone. “Thank you, Mr. Limond. I appreciate it. I trust you.”

I give him a curt nod. Inside, I don’t share that trust yet. But I’m determined to find something or anything that can cast reasonable doubt on his guilt. That’s my job, and reputation aside, I take it seriously.

Once he’s led out, Kidman and I exit the room. He waits until we’re outside, walking to the parking lot, to speak.

“What do you think?” he asks quietly.

I exhale. The morning sun is blinding after the jail’s fluorescent gloom. “I think he’s hiding something. Maybe not the murder, but something important.”

Kidman nods. “My thoughts too. Innocent people usually bend over backwards to help find the real culprit. He just kept insisting ‘I didn’t do it’ without offering any useful alternative.”

“Exactly.” I unlock my car and toss my notepad in the back. “I want a deep dive on that older son, Derek. And maybe any colleagues or neighbors with weird behavior. We need someone else to point a finger at, if possible.”

Kidman makes a note in his phone. “On it. I’ll also get a PI to canvass the neighborhood more to see if police missed anything.”

I run a hand through my hair. Fatigue is weighing on me, but oddly, the adrenaline of prepping a case is helping me push through. “Also, let’s subpoena Marjorie’s phone records. Maybe she had a secret that no one else knew. I have a gut feeling this case isn’t as cut-and-dry as it looks.”

Kidman raises an eyebrow. “Oh? You’ve got a theory?”

I rub my jaw. “Not a theory yet. Just… a sense that Mitchell’s hiding something about Marjorie. Maybe something that could shift blame. He was too emphatic and angry. Like he’s protecting someone. If not himself, then who?”

Kidman considers that. “You think it could be the son after all?”

I shrug. “It’s possible. Or someone completely off our radar. Either way, I intend to find out. We’re going to win this case, no matter what it takes.”

Saying that out loud, I feel a renewed spark of energy. This fight is just beginning, and I’m ready for it. In Charleston, fights like this are never clean, but if I drag some ugly truths out of the shadows to defend my client, so be it.

Kidman claps me on the back. “That’s what I like to hear, boss.”

I give him a faint grin and then slide into my car. As I drive out of the detention center lot, I notice my reflection in the rearview mirror, tired eyes, yes, but also a steely determination there. The adrenaline from the meeting is coursing through me. I live for challenges like this.

It’s only as I head toward the highway that I realize something surprising: I haven’t thought about the woman in the red dress all morning. The chaos of last night and the intensity of this case shoved that entirely aside.

But now, at a red light, her image creeps back into my mind. ADA Bridgette Leah, my opposing counsel. I feel an involuntary excitement at that prospect. In a few days, I’ll see her in court. It’s been a long time since a woman distracted me so much.

I shake my head, chastising myself. Focus, Park. I have bigger things to handle: an unwinnable murder case, a wife who’s furious with me, despite her brief cease-fire last night, and an ego to maintain. The last thing I need is to complicate it further by fantasizing about a rival attorney.`
