      content: `Park,  Saturday, May 9, Charleston Moss Golf Course (Afternoon)


I take a deep breath of the warm spring air and force a smile as I line up my shot on the 9th hole. The afternoon sun is high, and I can feel sweat trickling down my back, but the discomfort isn’t what’s throwing me off. It’s the conversation swirling around me.

“Hey, Park!”  Philip calls out with a grin, twirling his driver. “Saw the local news last night. You’re defending that sledgehammer killer, huh? Why on earth would you take on that case? The guy obviously offed his wife. That’s messed up, even if they’re paying you millions.”

The banter and laughter that had been bubbling among our group dies down. Eleven pairs of eyes shift to me, waiting. This again. Public opinion is already firmly against my client, and even some friends are judging me for representing him.

I plant my feet, resting my iron on my shoulder casually. With a light chuckle, I answer, “Well, Philip, you know how it is. Lawyers don’t exactly get to pick only the innocent clients. Bring me the money and I’ll defend the devil.” I raise an invisible toast. “To money, it rules the world!”

A few of the guys laugh, including Matthew, who chimes in, “Go get that bag, my man!” But not everyone is amused.

Philip, ever the outspoken one, is not finished. He practically spits on the grass. “You bloody capitalists. Licking the asses of the worst scum for a buck. Yuck!” He steps closer, glaring at me. “Have some shame, Park. Everyone knows that man killed his poor wife because she didn’t want his old ass anymore. And you’re trying to free him? You’d let a murderer walk among us just because he lined your pockets?”

I stiffen. For a moment, anger flares. Philip is a city councilman known for his moral grandstanding, and he loves an audience, which he has right now. I could verbally eviscerate him, but I hesitate. This is a friendly game; do I really want to cause a scene?

Before I find the words, Matthew steps in, bless him. He claps a hand on Philip’s shoulder. “Alright, alright, climb off that high horse. This is what lawyers do. If you have an issue, take it up with the justice system, not the guy doing his job.”

“And you,” Matthew adds in a lower voice to Philip, “are one to talk. You’re a politician making money off people’s taxes while doing squat most days. Don’t trash capitalism when you’re deep in it yourself.”

Some of the others snicker. Philip’s face flushes red in anger and embarrassment. He opens his mouth, but then snaps it shut, deciding better of it. Instead, he stomps off a few paces, muttering curses.

The tension slowly diffuses. A couple of the older men cough and change the subject back to the game, and our group splits to different spots as we continue playing.

I exhale slowly, adjusting my grip on the club. This is exactly what I needed to glean, though: a sense of public sentiment. If even my golf buddies think Mitchell is a monster, imagine the jury pool. This will be an uphill battle, I reflect.

I manage to finish the hole with par, but my focus is scattered. My thoughts drift to trial strategy one moment, then to Caroline the next, how furious she was at me only days ago, and how cunningly she derailed my big networking night. I still can’t believe I missed speaking with Chief Justice Roberts… That sting hasn’t faded. But I can’t exactly blame her; she was sick. Wasn’t she? A tiny doubt pokes at my mind. Caroline recovered remarkably fast from that ‘ulcer attack’,  and she’s been rather… chipper since.

I push that thought aside. I have more immediate concerns, like the fact that I just shot a bogey on the 10th because I was woolgathering.

Later, mercifully, the mood lightens again. By the 17th hole, everyone’s had a couple of beers from the cart, and we’re joking around again. Caroline rejoins us around that time, her garden meeting done, and as usual, she becomes the star of the show for a bit. The guys fawn and flirt harmlessly, and she soaks it up. I watch with a mix of pride and possessiveness; she’s gorgeous and charming when she wants to be, and I’m not blind to the envy some of these men have that I landed her.

“I wish Angela would join me after her meetings like you join Park,” Matthew laments. “But no, she runs home to the kids. Meanwhile, Caroline’s out here brightening our day.”

Caroline laughs lightly, sliding an arm around my waist as I stand beside her. I playfully squeeze her shoulder. All appears well. It’s almost enough to forget the turmoil of Wednesday night. Almost.

As our group wraps up the game (I didn’t win, thanks to my off performance, but Derek did, and won’t shut up about it), I glance across the club’s expanse toward the clubhouse patio. And my heart skips a beat.

There she is. Bridgette.

I hadn’t noticed her arrive, but she’s here, strolling alongside none other than Jerry Sullivan. They must’ve come while I was putting. Bridgette traded her red gown from the gala night for a casual chic ensemble this time. A white capri pants and a sky-blue sleeveless blouse, and she looks just as stunning. Maybe more so, because now she’s in my territory, my club, and she’s turning heads. Even some of my buddies pause to admire as she passes. A flicker of jealousy and excitement swirls in me.

Jerry spots our group and, of course, can’t resist. “Park Limond!” he calls, waddling over with a grin. “Fancy meeting you here. I guess even sharks need leisure.”.

He’s loud enough that a few nearby groups glance our way. I smirk. “Jerry, my friend! Didn’t expect to see you in a place where, you know, money is required. Inflation and gas prices treating that public servant salary okay?”

Some of my guys snort with laughter. Jerry’s face turns purple. Clearly, he’s sensitive about his finances. Before he can retort, Bridgette steps forward and speaks up. “Joking about things that hurt the masses isn’t a good look, Park. I expected better from a sharp mind like yours.”

Her voice is smooth and confident. It’s the first time I’ve heard her speak. I turn my attention fully to her, which was probably her intention, and it worked. Up close, I notice her eyes are a striking green.

I immediately feel a twinge of embarrassment for my jab now that she’s called me out. I raise my hands. “You’re right, that was in poor taste. My apologies,” I say, trying to sound genuine.

Bridgette’s stern expression softens. She offers her hand to me. “Hi, I’m Bridgette Leah. We haven’t officially met, though I believe we’ll be seeing a lot of each other in court soon.” She smiles. Polite, but with a hint of challenge in her eyes..

I clasp her hand, finding my voice. “Park Limond. Pleasure’s all mine. And yes, I’ve heard great things about you.” That part is true: gossip in legal circles travels fast, and apparently, Bridgette had a formidable record in New York before moving here.

She holds my handshake a beat longer than normal, her grip firm. “Likewise. Your reputation precedes you… Crown Prince.” She says the moniker in a lightly teasing tone. Then she adds, “I suppose I’ll be... learning from you on Monday.” The way she picks her words sends a little thrill through me. It almost sounds flirtatious, or is that my imagination?

My brain actually stalls. I forget to release her hand until I catch Caroline’s frown. 

“Hey, khaki shorts,” Caroline says brightly to Bridgette, using the fact that Bridgette is in golf attire as a cheeky address. She slides her arm through mine possessively. “I’m Caroline. Or better, Mrs. Limond, Park’s wife. In case you missed that.” She plasters on a wide smile, eyes cold. 

Oh boy. Bridgette raises her brows slightly and withdraws her hand from mine. “Of course,” she says with a polite smile that doesn’t reach her eyes. “Lovely to meet you, Mrs. Limond. I was just introducing myself to your husband professionally.”

“Of course,” Caroline echoes, still smiling that territorial smile.

The tension is palpable. A couple of the guys behind me mumble excuses and wander off to give space. Jerry just stands there smirking, clearly enjoying this little drama.

Bridgette takes a step back. “Well, we won’t intrude on your group. See you in court, Park.” She gives a final glance, this one just for me. A flicker of something in her eyes. Then, turns and heads back with Jerry toward the clubhouse bar.

I exhale deeply as Caroline immediately tugs me around to face her. “She’s pretty?” 

I know this tone. It’s a trap-laced statement. I tread carefully. “She’s alright,” I say with a shrug. “Doesn’t hold a candle to you, obviously.”

Caroline’s eyes search mine, as if hunting for any insincerity. I must have passed the test, because she nods and loops her arm through mine again, laying her head on my shoulder for a moment. “Good answer.”

I sigh inwardly. Crisis averted? Possibly.

With our golf outing effectively done, we all started leaving. On the way out, I see Bridgette in the distance chatting and laughing with a couple of older men from another group. She flips her hair and places a hand on one’s arm while laughing. I feel a prick of jealousy, which is absurd; she’s not mine to be jealous over. But the ease with which she’s charming them and how she occasionally flicks her gaze toward me indicates she knows exactly what she’s doing. She’s making a point: If I won’t flirt while wifey’s around, she has plenty of other targets.

Caroline, who hasn’t let go of me, notices my gaze and steers me firmly away, practically guiding me to our car. On the ride home, her mood is surprisingly neutral. Perhaps because I behaved, and she feels she’s made her dominance clear.

Yet, I can’t help sneaking one more thought about Bridgette as we drive off the club grounds: She’s going to be a formidable opponent in court and a dangerous distraction. And I have to be very careful, because Caroline absolutely picked up on the sparks there.

I stare out the window at the passing oaks draped in Spanish moss, trying to focus on the upcoming trial. Monday will be the opening hearing for the Mitchell case. The bail hearing, which means Bridgette might stand up and argue against me. The prospect strangely excites me more than it should. Time to get my head straight.

I force myself to run through legal strategies mentally, letting that drown out the persistent replay of Bridgette’s smile in my mind. Work, Park. Focus on work.

Little do I know, this delicate juggling act, between professional battles and personal temptations, is about to get far more complicated in the days to come.`
