      content: `Caroline, Tuesday, May 12, Limond Residence, Charleston (Morning)


Dawn breaks with a strange stillness in our house. I wake to pale light and the distant chirp of birds, but something feels off. Park’s side of the bed is empty. The sheets are cool, telling me he’s been up for a while. My stomach tightens with residual tension from the night before. Yesterday was… eventful, to put it mildly.

I throw on a silk robe and pad downstairs. I find my husband in the kitchen, standing rigidly by the counter with a cup of coffee untouched in his hand. He’s still in his pajamas, hair mussed as if he’s been running his fingers through it repeatedly. His gaze is fixed on the small TV mounted under the cabinets—the morning news.

When I see the headline banner crawling across the screen, I stop cold in the doorway. Assistant District Attorney Found Dead in Apparent Homicide. They’re talking about Bridgette.

Park notices me then. His eyes meet mine, and for a moment, neither of us speaks. In that silence, I see a storm of emotions in his face—shock, anger, maybe a flicker of guilt. I wonder how I look. My pulse is suddenly thundering in my ears as I step closer to the TV. A blonde reporter stands outside a brick apartment building downtown, microphone in hand. “…identified as thirty-two-year-old Bridgette Leah, a recent transfer to the Charleston District Attorney’s office. Police confirm they are investigating her death as a homicide. Sources say an early morning cleaning crew found Ms. Leah’s body late last night in the parking garage of her apartment complex. Authorities have not released details on cause of death, but an autopsy is scheduled. They also have not yet named a suspect, though an inside source indicates they are questioning a person of interest…”

“Oh my God,” I breathe, even though I’d known this was coming. Hearing it confirmed—seeing the building I recognize as Bridgette’s—sends a chill through me. This is real. She’s gone.

Park sets his coffee down with a shaky hand. “It broke an hour ago,” he says quietly. His voice is strained. “I—I had a bunch of missed calls from last night. One from Detective Anderson and a couple from Kidman. I guess they wanted to give me a heads-up before it hit the news.”

Detective Anderson—Matthew. That makes sense; Matthew would know Park had a connection to Bridgette. Kidman, too, given that he works with Park and likely heard some gossip. I’m almost relieved I slept through any late calls; the thought of Park getting that news in the middle of the night, in the dark with me asleep next to him, is unsettling. At least now it’s morning, and I’m here.

“I’m so sorry,” I say softly. It’s an automatic response, but I mean it. No matter how I felt about Bridgette personally—knowing she slept with my husband—this is horrific. No one deserves to be murdered. And I can’t ignore that if Ted’s suspicions are correct, Bridgette died tangled in something far larger than a jealous affair. Something I’ve now stepped into.

Park’s expression is guarded. He nods vaguely, eyes returning to the broadcast. The reporter continues, mentioning Bridgette’s notable cases. They even flash a photo of her—a professional headshot, all smart eyes and confident smile. I glance at Park; his jaw tightens at the sight. Does it hurt him, seeing her like that? I clamp down on the jealous thought. This isn’t the time.

Instead, I approach and gently touch his arm. “Are you okay?”

He lets out a breath through his nose. “I don’t… I can’t wrap my head around it.” He rubs his face. “We were just in court together yesterday morning. And now she’s—” He breaks off, shaking his head. “It’s surreal.”

His tone is flat, but I sense the turmoil roiling beneath. Park is compartmentalizing, something he does very well. Still, I catch a tremor in his hand as he picks up the coffee again. The strong facade is cracking.

I guide him to sit at the small breakfast table. He obeys mutely, sinking into a chair. I sit across from him. For a moment, it’s like we’re on the same side again, facing a problem together. I almost don’t know how to navigate that feeling after so much strife.

“This is going to be a circus,” he mutters after a moment, staring into the middle distance. “The press, the courthouse… It’s already all over the news.”

He’s right. Bridgette’s death will explode in Charleston’s legal community. She wasn’t famous, but her role in a high-profile murder trial and her connection—personal connection—to Park, the “Crown Prince” of those courtrooms, is gossip gold. And I recall from yesterday’s hearing that whispers of Park’s affair had already spread. Now the woman he cheated with has been murdered? People will be ravenous for details. My skin prickles imagining the looks I’ll get. The pitying, curious stares. Yesterday at the bail hearing was bad enough. Today will be ten times worse.

I swallow, pushing aside my own discomfort. “Have the police said anything to you yet?”

He nods vaguely. “Matthew left a voicemail… he said he’d like me to come in today to answer a few questions, since I—since we had a known… friendship.” The euphemism for an affair hangs unspoken. “It’s routine.”

Of course. They’ll interview the husband and the lover first. The fact that Park was with her intimately, and I’m the betrayed spouse—those are classic motives in homicide cases. My chest constricts. Could I be on their list, too? A scorned wife is a suspect that leaps to mind. Do they suspect me? The thought is horrifying, yet I maintain a neutral face.

Park seems to read my mind. He suddenly reaches across and takes my hand. “They might want to talk to you as well, Caro,” he says carefully. “Standard procedure. I told Matthew I’d bring it up to you.”

I nod, squeezing his hand. “I understand. I’ll cooperate. I have nothing to hide.”

It’s true—I didn’t kill Bridgette. But I do have something to hide: my connection with the person likely suspected of killing her. The person of interest the reporter mentioned is almost certainly Ted. I feel a twist of worry. Have they picked him up already? Questioned him? If so, he didn’t mention that during our meeting. He implied he was lying low. Perhaps they haven’t found him yet or are building their case.

And then there’s the GPS tracker in my purse, upstairs. The one Ted “dropped.” A memento of yesterday’s clandestine alliance. I hadn’t decided what to do with it yet. Definitely not something I want the police stumbling across if they, say, search my belongings for any reason.

I rise, patting Park’s shoulder. “Let me get dressed. I’ll go down to the station with you.”

“You don’t have to—” he begins.

“I want to,” I insist gently. “We should both make statements and… and put this behind us.” I catch myself; of course, for him this won’t be so simple as putting it behind. But we need to address it head-on. “Besides, I’d rather face whatever gossip or questions together.”

A flicker of gratitude crosses his face. “Alright. Thank you.”

As I head upstairs to change, I pause by the bannister, out of Park’s sight. My heart is pounding. If I go to the police station, I might cross paths with Ted if they’ve brought him in. What would I do? Acknowledge him? Pretend not to know him? And what if Park finds out how well I know Ted?

No. One thing at a time. I hurry to the bedroom. As I dress in a somber black blouse and slacks, I shoot a quick text to Ted: Saw the news. Are you safe?

I hesitate, then add: Park and I are heading to the police station soon to give statements. It might be risky to volunteer that, but I want him to be prepared in case our paths cross. I’m not sure he’d show up there voluntarily, but if they’ve summoned him…

A response pings back within a minute. I snatch up my phone. Ted: Safe. Lying low. Thanks for the heads-up. Good luck with cops. Will touch base later.

Relief loosens a knot in my chest. At least he’s not in custody. And he knows I’m thinking of him. I type back quickly: Be careful. Don’t do anything risky.

He doesn’t reply immediately, which is fine. Park’s calling up the stairs, asking if I’m ready. I slip the phone into my purse. My fingers brush the hard little plastic of the tracker device. After a second’s thought, I tuck it into the back of my lingerie drawer, beneath silk and lace that no officer is likely to rifle through unless they have a warrant. If asked, I’d prefer to simply not mention it. It’s not directly relevant right now—and if I do need it later, I know where it is.

I meet Park downstairs. He’s changed into a suit—a charcoal gray one that softens the pallor of his face. He looks handsome but exhausted. We exchange a wordless glance that contains a lot: apprehension, unity, lingering hurt. So many swirling undercurrents between us, but we present a united front as we leave the house side by side.

The drive to the station is silent aside from the talk radio droning low. They, too, are discussing Bridgette’s murder. “...unconfirmed reports suggest Leah may have been struck by a heavy object. There are also rumors of chemical agents used to destroy evidence at the scene. In a bizarre twist, sources say investigators are looking into a relative of the victim—”

I quickly reach over and switch off the radio. My pulse spikes. Chemical agents used to destroy evidence... a relative of the victim... Ted’s words from yesterday echo in my mind: DNA wiped with chemicals, they’re framing me. And now the media hints at the same. They’re onto him. My palms dampen.

Park glances at me, puzzled by my sudden action. I force a thin smile. “Sorry. Couldn’t listen to them speculate anymore.”

He nods, misunderstanding my anxiety as discomfort about Bridgette's gossip. “Yeah. It’s all noise.” He returns his eyes to the road, sighing. “They mentioned a relative. Did Bridgette have family here?”

My throat tightens. This is it. Park might be putting pieces together right now. I will keep my face neutral. “I don’t know,” I lie softly. “I remember hearing she had an older sister up north. Not sure about anyone else.”

He hums noncommittally, but I can see the gears turning. Don’t think too hard about it, Park. The last thing I need is him connecting “relative of the victim” to the Ted who’s been texting me. But I suspect it’s already too late. His fingers flex on the steering wheel, a telltale sign of his agitation.

We arrive at the Charleston Police Department downtown. As we walk in, Park’s hand hovers at my lower back—a gentlemanly habit, guiding me—but he doesn’t actually touch me. We’re not quite okay. I brace myself as a young detective escorts us to an interview room.

Matthew Anderson joins us within minutes. He greets us professionally, but there’s warmth in his eyes when he looks at me. “Caroline, Park—thanks for coming in.” His gaze lingers on me, concern evident. Matthew’s a family friend; he attended our wedding. He must know how awkward this is.

We each give our statements separately. I go first. Matthew keeps it fairly brief, clearly not considering me a serious suspect. I explain that at the time of Bridgette’s likely murder (estimated early afternoon yesterday), I was out having lunch and then “running errands.” I stick as close to the truth as possible without incriminating myself. I do mention I took on a former pro-bono client for a counseling session earlier that day, in case they can trace my whereabouts and wonder. Matthew notes it without much comment. He doesn’t ask the client’s name, surprisingly. Maybe he assumes it’s irrelevant to Bridgette’s case. Or perhaps he already knows or suspects and is waiting to see if I volunteer it. If he does suspect Ted, he might be aware I talked to him. But nothing in Matthew’s polite demeanor gives it away.

He asks gently if I ever met or spoke to Bridgette outside of public encounters. I truthfully say no—we only ever interacted briefly at a golf course and courthouse in plain view of others. I admit I was angry at her due to the affair, but I emphasize that I was committed to working things out with Park. “I would never harm her,” I say quietly. “I might have disliked her, but I’m a therapist—I help people. Violence is not in my character.”

Matthew nods sympathetically. “Understood. We have to ask, given the circumstances. But this is just a formality, Caroline.”

When I’m done, I catch a glimpse of Park through the one-way glass as I exit. He’s sitting stiffly at the table, hands clasped, as another detective—one I don’t recognize—is about to question him. I’m not allowed to sit in, of course. So I wait in the hallway, heart in my throat, imagining what they’re asking my husband. About his affair. About where he was yesterday. About me.

It’s agonizing not knowing. After nearly half an hour, Park emerges, face drawn. Matthew follows him out, offering a friendly pat on the shoulder. “Thanks, buddy. We’ll be in touch if we need anything else.”

Park nods, then tilts his head toward me. “We good to go?”

“Yes.” Matthew gives me a brief, reassuring smile. “Thank you, Caroline. I’m sure this is tough on you too.” There’s meaning behind his eyes. Does he suspect the toll this is taking on our marriage? Or perhaps he’s cautioning me—maybe he knows more about Ted than he let on.

“Take care, Matt,” I murmur.

We walk out into the bright mid-morning sun. Park is silent until we reach the car. The moment we’re both inside, doors shut, he exhales a loud breath. “Well. That’s done.” He sounds exhausted.

“How did it go?” I venture carefully.

He slides on his sunglasses, obscuring his eyes. “Fine. Routine questions. My whereabouts, the last time I saw or spoke to her.” He hesitates, then adds quietly, “They asked about you, of course. If I thought you might’ve confronted her out of… anger.”

A cold sliver of dread runs through me. “What did you say?”

He glances at me as if offended I’d even ask. “I told them absolutely not. That you would never do something like that.” He pauses. “I also volunteered that we were together all last night, in case they were fishing for your alibi then.”

He covered for me, unprompted. I bite the inside of my cheek, guilt mixing with gratitude. After everything, he still protects me instinctively.

A beat passes. Then Park clears his throat. “They, uh, did mention a person of interest.” His tone is careful, but edged. “Bridgette’s brother.”

My pulse skips. Here it comes. I keep my face as still as I can. “Oh?”

He nods, fingers drumming once on the steering wheel. “Apparently her brother’s in town. Theodore Leah. He might’ve been around her apartment yesterday. They’re looking at him closely.”

I feign appropriate surprise. “Her brother? I never knew she had a brother until now.”

Park doesn’t respond immediately. The air between us thickens. I can sense him watching me from behind those dark lenses. My heart thuds, but I maintain a puzzled frown, as if processing the news.

Finally, he simply says, “Yes. It surprised me too.” He starts the ignition.

The ride back is oppressively quiet. I feel questions bubbling up unspoken. By the time we get home, it’s nearly noon. Park pulls into our driveway and kills the engine. Before I can open my door, he says tightly, “So. You had a session with a client yesterday.”

My hand freezes on the handle. I turn slowly. His sunglasses are off now; he left them in the cupholder. I meet his naked eyes, blue and burning, and my stomach flips. He knows—at least, he suspects.

I wet my lips. “Yes. I told you last night—one of my former patients reached out.”

“And this former patient’s name?” he asks, too casually.

My mouth goes dry. “Park…”

He holds up a hand, jaw clenched. “Don’t. Don’t treat me like one of your therapy cases. Just answer.”

I straighten my spine. “That’s confidential. You know I can’t disclose client information, even informally, without permission.”

His expression twists in disbelief. “Oh, cut the crap, Caroline! You were a therapist, yes, but you’re not practicing officially right now. This isn’t some random patient from years ago. This is someone you met with off the books while lying to me about having lunch with friends.” His voice is rising with each sentence, anger pouring out. “Or am I wrong? Did you not lie to my face about meeting Lily so you could sneak off with—” He bites back whatever word he nearly said.

My heart hammers. We’re doing this now, apparently. I feel a surge of defensiveness. “I didn’t want to tell you then because it was personal. That client needed privacy—”

“Bullshit.” Park slams his palm on the steering wheel, startling me. “You didn’t tell me because you knew it would look bad! And guess what? It does. It looks incredibly damn bad, Caroline.” His eyes glitter with hurt and fury. “I trusted that you were where you said you’d be. Meanwhile you were off with some man—God knows where—giving ‘pro-bono therapy sessions’?” He practically spits the last words.

I bristle. “Yes, that’s exactly what I was doing. Therapy. Listening. Helping. Not screwing around behind your back, if that’s what you’re insinuating.”

He laughs harshly. “Am I supposed to just take your word for it? After you deliberately deceived me about it in the first place?”

My temper flares. “You really want to have the honesty conversation, Park? With me?”

He flinches, a flush creeping up his neck. I know I’ve hit below the belt, but anger has me in its grip now. Months of resentment threaten to boil over.

We glare at each other in the confines of the car. His hands are clenched white-knuckled on his knees. My own are trembling.

Finally, through gritted teeth, he asks, “Was it him?”

“Who?” I say, even though I know exactly who.

He exhales sharply through his nose. “Don’t play dumb. Theodore. Bridgette’s brother. Was he the ‘client’ you met yesterday?”

I hesitate a moment too long. That’s an answer enough. Park makes a sound of bitter disgust and moves to throw open his door. Panicking, I grab his arm. “Wait—Park—”

He shakes me off, stepping out into the driveway. I scramble out of my side and circle the car to him. “Let me explain!”

He whirls on me. “Explain? Oh, this I’ve got to hear.” Sarcasm drips from each syllable. “Because from where I’m standing, my wife has been secretly meeting with the brother of the woman I—” He stops, choking on the words. “The brother of the murder victim, who by the way is suspected of killing her. And you’re—what? Befriending him?”

“I’m counseling him,” I say firmly. “And he’s not what they think, Park. He’s—”

“A suspected murderer?” Park interjects, eyes blazing. “And possibly using you. God, Caroline, do you even realize how dangerous that could be?”

I cross my arms over my chest. “He didn’t hurt her. I believe him. He’s being framed.”

Park stares at me like I’ve grown a second head. “Listen to yourself. You’ve known this man for, what, a few days? And you take his word over the collective investigation of the police department? Over common sense?”

“Common sense?” My voice rises. “What about my professional sense? I have training in evaluating people, remember? Ted’s story holds weight. He’s genuinely distraught, Park. He lost his sister and now he’s being set up to take the fall. Someone is framing him—someone with power.”

Park throws up his hands. “Oh, right. Let me guess—he thinks the boogeyman did it. Or maybe he’s spinning some conspiracy theory about powerful folks being out to get him? How convenient.”

I narrow my eyes. “Actually, yes. He suspects someone highly connected might be behind it.”

Park’s laugh is incredulous. “Sure. Let’s blame some nameless cabal, that’s easier than accepting he might have just done it himself. Caroline, he is the obvious suspect: he has a criminal record, no real alibi, and likely some grievance or mental instability. It’s textbook. Of course he’s charming you into believing him. Probably to get information on me or the case—did you consider that? Maybe he approached you deliberately, knowing who you were.”

The suggestion hits a sore spot, because it’s one I’d briefly considered on Saturday. But I shake it off. “If you’d spoken with him, you’d know that’s not true. Ted didn’t even realize who I was at first.”

Park barks out another humorless laugh. “He’s got you completely snowed. Jesus, Caroline, this is unreal. Are you actually trusting the brother of—” He cuts himself off, but I know what he was going to say: the brother of the woman I cheated with.

I finish it for him, bitterly. “The brother of your mistress? Yes, I am talking to him. Because you know what? Someone needed to. The cops sure as hell aren’t listening to him, and obviously you aren’t either. The great Park Limond has decided he’s guilty, case closed.”

Park’s nostrils flare. “Don’t twist this around on me. I am trying to keep you safe, Caroline. This man is dangerous, whether he killed her or not. He’s angry and desperate—two things that get people hurt. And you’re sneaking off, lying to me, to spend time with him? How do you think that makes me feel?”

“How did you think your sneaking around made me feel?” I snap. The dam breaks; months of pain surge in my chest. “You have the gall to talk about lying and sneaking as if you didn’t shatter my trust first! I am doing what I have to, Park. What I choose to, for myself. I won’t apologize for helping someone in need, especially given how all of this,” I gesture wildly, “started because of you and her!”

He recoils as if slapped. “I know that,” he says, voice rough. “You think I don’t know what I did? I regret it every damn day. But trying to punish me by putting yourself at risk like this—”

“This isn’t about punishing you!” I shout. “Not everything I do is some reaction to your betrayal. Maybe I have my own purpose here. Maybe I actually care that an innocent person might be railroaded and the real killer walking free. I’m sorry if that doesn’t align neatly with your priorities.”

Park’s eyes blaze. “My priorities? What do you think I’m doing, Caroline? I’m busting my ass on the Mitchell case—trying to ensure an innocent man doesn’t go to prison for something he didn’t do!”

I let out a sharp bark of laughter. “Innocent? Aaron Mitchell? How sure are you about that, really? Because it sounds like you’ve started considering alternate suspects like his son Derek.” I throw the name like a challenge, and I see from Park’s stunned face that I’ve hit a bullseye. “Oh yes, I know about Derek,” I press. “Heard whispers. So don’t act high and mighty about me chasing the truth when you’re doing the same in your realm.”

He steps closer, lowering his voice dangerously. “The difference is, I’m doing it through the legal system. I’m not gallivanting around playing detective and breaking God-knows-how-many ethical lines to do it.”

The air between us vibrates with anger. My nails bite into my palms. “If you can look me in the eye and tell me you’ve never crossed a line for something you believed in, I’ll back off,” I say quietly. “But we both know that’s not the case, Mr. Crown Prince. You bend rules all the time to win.”

His face flushes. “That’s law. That’s my job.”

“And this is my job—helping people. Ted is my patient, Park. He came to me for help, and I won’t abandon him because it makes you uncomfortable.”

We stand there breathing hard, glaring. I can hear the blood rushing in my ears. This might be the worst fight we’ve ever had—quiet bedroom arguments and icy stares have nothing on the raw fury sparking here in broad daylight, right in our driveway.

Park breaks first. He turns away, raking both hands through his hair. When he looks at me again, his eyes glisten with angry tears. The sight punctures something in me. It’s rare to see him like this, unguarded pain on full display.

“You’re my wife,” he says unsteadily. “I’m supposed to protect you. But I feel like I’m losing you piece by piece—to your anger at me, and now to… to him. And I’m terrified, Caroline.” His voice cracks. “I’m terrified that my screw-ups have pushed you straight into someone else’s arms, or into harm’s way, or both. And I can’t do a damn thing about it because I have no right to demand your trust.”

My throat tightens. Damn him for saying exactly the words that could pierce my armor. Tears blur my vision. “Park—”

He lifts a hand. “I’m not finished.” He takes a breath. “If you truly believe Ted is innocent, fine. But do you really think you can be his savior alone? Let the police handle finding the real culprit. If he’s innocent, that will come out.”

I shake my head. “I’m not so sure it will. You’ve seen how things go—sometimes the innocent get screwed. You’re fighting that in court right now. Why is this any different?”

“Because you’re personally involved in a way that could get you hurt!” he nearly shouts. “I cheated on you. I betrayed you. But I never put you in physical danger, Caroline. Not until now, indirectly, with all this madness.”

The mention of danger triggers a memory of that unmarked car I thought I saw behind me last night on the drive back from meeting Ted. I’m not sure it was anything, but still. I soften my tone, trying a new approach. “Park, I hear you. I do. I know you’re worried. But I promise, I’m being careful. I’m not going to do anything reckless. Ted and I… we’re just talking through strategies, trying to find evidence. If we find something concrete, I’ll encourage him to bring it to the police. I will.”

He searches my face, uncertainty etched in his. “You will, huh? And what if this ‘evidence’ implicates someone powerful, as he claims? What then? You think the police will just roll out the red carpet to nail an influential suspect based on some vigilante amateur hour investigation?”

I bristle slightly at “amateur hour,” but temper my response. “That’s why we have to be smart about it. Get proof that’s undeniable.”

Park shakes his head, a look of despairing disbelief on his face. “Listen to us. This is insane. We shouldn’t be on opposite sides, Caroline.” His voice goes quiet. “I can’t take it. Not on top of everything else.”

The raw hurt in his words drains the fight out of me. My own anger ebbs, leaving exhaustion and sadness. He’s right—we’re on the same team, or we should be. We both want justice in our own ways. We both want our marriage to survive, deep down.

I step forward, cautiously reaching for his hand. He allows it, our fingers interlacing almost by muscle memory. “We’re not on opposite sides,” I say softly. “I’m sorry I lied about meeting him. I should have told you. I just… I knew how it would look, and I couldn’t handle another explosion then. I thought I could manage it on my own.”

Park’s thumb strokes my hand absentmindedly. “Caroline, handling things on your own is kind of a pattern with you. You shut me out.”

I bite my lip. “Maybe because when I let you in, I got hurt.”

He squeezes his eyes shut. “I know. I have no one to blame but myself for that.” He opens them again, pleading. “But I’m asking you, please, don’t shut me out of this. If you insist on… on helping Ted, then at least keep me in the loop. Let me help you, or protect you if needed. I can’t just watch you walk into danger blind.”

His request hangs in the warm air. This is what I wanted, isn’t it? For him to respect what I’m doing and even offer support. But there’s a catch: telling him everything means betraying Ted’s confidence, and potentially scaring Park into going to the police or locking me up at home. Yet continuing to hide it will drive us further apart. And maybe get me in deeper trouble if I misstep.

I realize with a pang that I want Park’s help. Yesterday, I relished keeping my own secret mission; today, standing here with him, I just feel weary. The thought of carrying this burden alone is suddenly too heavy. Perhaps we’d fare better combining our efforts.

“You’d help?” I ask warily. “Even with how you feel about him?”

Park grimaces. “I still think he’s likely guilty. But I trust your instincts enough to at least not dismiss your belief. And frankly, if there is some greater threat here, I’d rather we tackle it together.” He pauses. “Besides, I have resources you don’t. Legal avenues. Investigators. If something is there to be found, I can try.”

My mind whirls. Park’s PI digging into Derek was already a huge step; he likely has info I haven’t seen. If Park shared that with me—do I dare dream? This might be the bridge between our two quests. And working together on something, after so long being at odds, could either heal us or break us completely.

I take a deep breath. “Okay. I’ll tell you everything. But not out here.” I glance around our front yard, realizing we’ve been having this heated conversation in plain view. Thankfully, our nearest neighbor is a good acre away and likely at work, but still. “Let’s go inside.”

He nods, and we walk hand in hand into the house. There’s a tentative truce in that small physical connection.

We settle on the living room couch. I notice Park’s discarded coffee mug from earlier on a side table, untouched and cold. So much has happened in just a few hours.

True to my word, I start from the beginning: running into Ted on Saturday at the Garden Society event (I omit that Ted initially confronted me when he suspected Park—I frame it as a chance meeting where he recognized me as a therapist), the conversation at the bail hearing, and our session in the park. I relay his story—the mysterious, powerful enemies, the evidence of tampering, his claim of being framed.

Park listens intently, interrupting only a few times with pointed questions. His frown deepens when I describe the tracking device Ted had (I even retrieve it from upstairs to show him). By the time I catch up to today, I’m emotionally drained all over again. But the weight on my shoulders is lighter now that it’s shared.

Park turns the little GPS tracker between his fingers thoughtfully. “He gave this to you, then changed his mind?”

“I’m not entirely sure,” I admit. “He left it behind. It could’ve been an accident or deliberate. Either way, he hasn’t asked for it back.”

Park sets it down. “If he was following me as a suspect at first, that might have been to plant on my car or something. But then the timeline evidence cleared me, so he didn’t bother.” His tone is matter-of-fact, but I catch the flicker of guilt in his eyes at the mention of being a suspect.

“He was pretty upfront that he wondered about you initially,” I say gently. “It made sense—statistically speaking, spouses or lovers are usually the first suspects. And with the affair... well.” I manage not to sound accusatory. It’s just a fact.

Park grimaces. “Right.” He rubs his brow. “This is all so twisted. I have to say, as crazy as his theory sounds, some things line up. The wiped evidence, for one. That’s not common, and it implies planning. If someone did set him up, they were thorough.”

Hope sparks faintly in my chest. Park’s analytical side is engaging, weighing possibilities. He hasn’t outright dismissed Ted’s claims. That’s huge.

“There’s more,” I say. “He hinted strongly that he suspects the Mitchell family might be involved. That Bridgette ‘messed up their plans’ somehow. I thought of Derek, or maybe someone in Aaron’s family.”

Park’s eyes widen a fraction. “He mentioned the Mitchells by name?”

“Not explicitly. But he said ‘powerful family’. And you know as well as I do, the Mitchells have clout in this town.” I lean forward. “Park, do the Mitchells have any sway in law enforcement? Or any known underhanded dealings?”

He considers. “Aaron Mitchell’s father is an influential businessman, semi-retired. Old Charleston money, country club board member—the type who slaps backs with police chiefs and councilmen. But he’s in his seventies. Hardly picturing him ordering an assassination.” Park’s brow furrows. “Aaron has two brothers—older one Franklin, who runs the family company now, and younger one, Peter, on some bank board. They’re wealthy, connected for sure. Whether any of them are the type to murder someone… that’s a stretch. But powerful family, yes.”

I absorb that. So there are multiple Mitchell men with resources, aside from Derek. Could Ted suspect one of them? Or perhaps Derek is acting with their backing? “What about Derek? He’s not powerful himself, but he’s their blood.”

Park purses his lips. “Derek’s not powerful. But if Franklin or the father wanted to protect Aaron, they might quietly bankroll an off-the-books solution.” He says it like he hates even considering it. “Still, it’s conjecture. And why target Bridgette, specifically? She was just one ADA—Jerry could carry on the case. Unless she found something outside the main case that threatened them.”

I think of what that could be. Maybe Bridgette discovered evidence that Aaron was innocent and Derek guilty, and someone in the family silenced her? But if they wanted to protect Aaron, revealing Derek as the killer would also exonerate Aaron. Unless protecting the family name meant not letting anyone know that a Mitchell murdered another family member. That’s twisted, but possible—they might prefer Aaron take the fall quietly rather than expose the family scandal of the son killing stepmom. Good grief.

I voice the thought. Park’s face pales slightly. “That’s… incredibly dark. But these sorts of dynasties care about legacy above all. Having Aaron in prison for wife’s murder is bad, but maybe they thought they could overturn it on appeal. Exposing that the brother killed her? That’s forever a stain in the history books.”

My heart beats faster. “So maybe Bridgette stumbled on evidence pointing to Derek as the wife’s killer, and someone silenced her to keep it buried.”

Park presses his fingers to his eyes. “But that would mean they set up their own son, Aaron, to take the blame. You’re talking about sacrificing one son to protect the other and the family name. That’s monstrous.”

I recall the portrait of the Mitchell clan I’ve seen in society pages—patriarch Richard Mitchell with his grown children standing stiff and formal. They did project a rather cold, old-money vibe. “It’s monstrous, yes. But not impossible.”

“True.” He sighs. “I can’t believe I’m even entertaining this.” Then he gives me a tentative look. “I have something to share, too. I was going to anyway, for the case, but now it seems more urgent.”

He grabs his briefcase from by the couch and pulls out a file. “Our private investigator dug up some significant info on Derek yesterday.”

I lean in as he opens it. There are notes and printed receipts. “He traced Derek’s movements. Derek indeed left Nashville around April 26. We have a credit card hit in Savannah, GA on April 27, and security footage from a motel outside Charleston showing his car in the parking lot late on April 27.” Park taps a grainy still image clipped in the file—a dark SUV that could belong to anyone, but presumably matches Derek’s registration. “Marjorie was killed the night of April 28. If Derek was in the area, that’s huge. We don’t have proof he stayed through the 28th yet—no receipts on the exact day. But the PI is looking for toll booth records or traffic cams that might place him on the 28th.”

My eyes widen. “Park, that’s… that’s basically a smoking gun if you get confirmation he was here during the murder.”

He nods grimly. “Yeah. I intended to use it in trial to raise reasonable doubt. At the very least, to force the prosecution on their back foot. They have no idea we have this.” He runs a hand through his hair. “I was actually going to subpoena Derek to testify, to see if he lies about his whereabouts and then nail him with this evidence. Risky, but I’m pretty sure he’d slip up.”

My pulse quickens. “Do you think Derek actually did kill his stepmother?”

Park exhales slowly. “Honestly… yes, I think it’s very possible. The motive fits—a history of resentment, maybe money or inheritance issues, who knows. And his behavior afterward was off; I recall Aaron said Derek barely showed up for the funeral.” He flips a page in the file where a typewritten interview summary shows that Aaron noted Derek’s distance. “We were focusing so much on Aaron that Derek flew under the radar.”

I chew my lip. “If Derek did it, and the family found out, maybe they closed ranks to protect him. Perhaps even Aaron would take the fall out of misguided loyalty, or at the family’s insistence to keep Derek out of prison.”

“That’s a hell of a sacrifice,” Park mutters. “Aaron hired me to fight, though. He swears he’s innocent and wants out. If he knew Derek did it, why not tell me? Unless he’s being coerced into silence.”

“Coerced or manipulated. Family pressure can be immense, especially in those circles. They might have convinced him a public scandal of that nature would ruin everything and maybe promised to quietly get him off later.”

Park shakes his head in disbelief at the Machiavellian scenario we’re painting. But I see reluctant acceptance in his eyes. It holds together. “If that’s true, then whoever killed Bridgette could indeed be connected. Maybe she uncovered some link to Derek and was going to bring it up. Or maybe Ted is right and she was messing up the Mitchells’ plan by pushing too hard for conviction, threatening to expose the truth inadvertently.”

I feel a chill. “So they—whoever ‘they’ are—killed her and framed Ted to neatly tie off the loose end.”

Park grimaces. “It’s possible.” Then he fixes me with a stern look. “All the more reason you and Ted need to stay out of their crosshairs. If these people are willing to kill an ADA and let an innocent man hang, they won’t hesitate to hurt anyone who pries.”

He reaches over and takes my shoulders, leaning forward earnestly. “Caroline, promise me something. Now that I’m looped in… please promise you won’t go digging further without telling me. If you get a tip or something, you call me or Detective Anderson. Don’t go meet any mysterious sources alone, don’t try to confront anyone by yourself. Please.”

I put my hand over his. The desperate concern on his face is genuine. Despite everything, he does truly care. “I promise,” I say softly. “No reckless moves. And I’ll make sure Ted stays cautious too.”

Park’s eyes darken slightly at the mention of Ted, but he nods. “Fine.” After a beat, he asks, “Where is he now? Did he tell you his plans?”

I hesitate. Ted didn’t specify, just said he was safe and lying low. “I’m not sure. He’s likely staying out of sight until he can find proof or until… well, until something breaks.”

Park purses his lips. “If he’s innocent, he should actually let himself be taken in for questioning rather than run. Running makes him look guilty and could escalate things.”

“He’s scared, Park. He doesn’t trust the system to be fair to him. And given what we’re theorizing, maybe he’s right.”

Park sighs. “Maybe.” He glances at the clock on the wall. It’s past noon now, and I realize he hasn’t even eaten breakfast. Neither have I. We’re running on adrenaline and fumes.

Before I can suggest lunch, his phone buzzes. He checks it and stands abruptly. “It’s Kidman, I need to take this.”

He steps into the foyer to answer. I lean back on the couch, exhaling deeply. My mind is spinning with all we’ve shared. It feels like we just unknotted a nasty tangle between us—only to reveal an even larger knot of conspiracy beyond. But at least we’re facing it together now. That thought buoys me.

After a few minutes, Park returns, tucking his phone away. He looks conflicted. “That was about the trial. They want to move forward as scheduled, starting tomorrow morning, despite—” he gestures vaguely, “everything.”

Of course. The world doesn’t stop for Bridgette’s death. “Are you ready for that?” I ask gently. “After all this?”

His eyes harden with resolve. “More than ever. If our theory is right, getting Aaron acquitted could expose Derek—or flush out whoever’s pulling strings. I need to win this.”

I nod, admiring his determination. “You will.” I believe it; Park is at his best in the courtroom. And now he has extra fire.

He sits beside me again. “Kidman’s finishing a motion about excluding some evidence. But I suspect prosecution might try to delay using Bridgette’s death as an excuse.” He rubs his chin. “Jerry Sullivan loved Bridgette like a mentee; he might request a continuance out of ‘grief’ or to reassign a prosecutor.”

“Would a judge allow it?”

“Hard to say. Could go either way. But if they delay, that gives Derek and whoever more time to cover their tracks. I’d rather strike now.” Park’s jaw sets. “I won’t let them stall into obscurity.”

A surge of admiration and affection wells up in me—feelings that have been buried under hurt for too long. This is the man I fell in love with: passionate, relentless when fighting for justice. Flashes of that righteous man have shown through even in our roughest times, and here he is fully returned. My heart aches, realizing how much I missed him.

I reach out and straighten his slightly crooked tie, a small gesture of care. “If the trial proceeds tomorrow, I’ll be there,” I say quietly.

He searches my face. “You don’t have to—”

“I want to.” I manage a tiny smile. “You’ll need someone in your corner, right? All those whispers and eyes… I can handle it.”

His shoulders slump with relief. Gently, he takes my hand from his tie and presses it against his cheek. The stubble of a day’s stress scratches my palm. He closes his eyes briefly. “Thank you,” he whispers.

We stay like that for a long moment, foreheads almost touching. Tentatively, I rest my head on his shoulder. I feel his arm wrap around me, drawing me in. The warmth of his body, the familiar scent of him—God, I’ve yearned for this closeness even when I swore I didn’t.

“I’m sorry,” he murmurs into my hair. “For everything.”

“I know,” I whisper back. “Me too.”

We’re not magically fixed—far from it. But this fragile peace between us feels like a turning point. United by adversity, maybe we can find our way back to each other fully.

After a few minutes, Park tilts my chin up and kisses my forehead softly. “I have to get back to the office soon,” he says, regretful. “Finish prepping for tomorrow.”

I nod, pulling back and wiping the moisture from my eyes. “Of course.” I stand up, regathering myself. “I’ll make you a sandwich to take. You’re running on empty.”

He smiles, a ghost of his old playful smirk. “I won’t say no to that.”

In the kitchen, I busy myself assembling a quick lunch for him—turkey on rye, one of his favorites. He hovers nearby, watching me with an unreadable expression. Maybe marveling at this domestic normalcy after the blowout we just had. Honestly, I’m marveling too.

As I wrap the sandwich, he asks, “Will you be alright here? Not planning any solo missions or secret meetings while I’m gone?”

His tone is light, but I detect genuine concern. I offer a reassuring smile. “I’ll be fine. I might reach out to Ted later, let him know some progress. But I’ll do it from right here at home.”

Park nods slowly. “Okay.” He hesitates. “Tell him… tell him I’m looking into things too. And that—for what it’s worth—I’m sorry for his loss.” The words come out stiff, but sincere enough. I’m a bit surprised; it’s a gracious gesture.

“I’ll tell him,” I say softly.

A few minutes later, I walk Park to the door. Before leaving, he cups my face and kisses me—lightly on the lips, a question in the contact. I answer by kissing him back, gentle and lingering. When we part, we share a tentative smile.

“I’ll see you in court, counselor,” I say, attempting a light tease.

He brushes a strand of hair behind my ear. “See you then, love.” The endearment warms me to my toes.

And then he’s off, striding to his car with squared shoulders, rearmed for battle. I watch until he drives away, then close the door and lean against it, exhaling a long breath. It feels like we just survived an earthquake and are left standing, albeit shakily. But now, at least, I’m not standing alone.

After tidying up and nibbling some crackers (my appetite is still anxious), I settle on the couch with my phone. Time to check on Ted. I text: Are you alright? Update: Park knows I’ve been helping you. He’s actually on board to find the truth now. We suspect Derek Mitchell is involved. Be very careful.

He replies within a minute: I’m okay. Lying low at a friend’s place. That’s big news about Park. Didn’t expect that. Derek, huh? Makes sense. I have a lead on something related. Can we meet tonight? Need to show you in person.

My heart kicks. A lead? I type: Yes. But caution, if they’re watching me, the meeting might tip them off.

His response: Understood. Not at your house. How about Centennial Park again, 8 PM? Quieter at night. I’ll be in disguise ;)

Despite the weight of everything, I smile at the winking emoji he appends. Alright. I’ll be there. You'd better be in a damn good disguise, I don’t need to be seen with “a wanted man” 😉.

Ted: I’ll be a ghost. See you then, Doc.

I put down the phone, my mind already racing. Whatever he’s found must be important if he wants to meet in person at night. I trust he’ll be careful, but I’ll have to be as well. I made a promise to Park not to do anything reckless. Is this reckless? Meeting in public might be, given Ted’s status. But Centennial Park is a big open area; we can keep it brief.

And maybe—I think with a burst of inspiration—I should loop in backup just in case. Someone who can watch from a distance. Perhaps Park? But he’ll be buried in trial prep till late. And involving him directly might spook Ted if he sees him. No… perhaps Matthew? He told us to keep him informed. If I tell Matthew that I’m meeting an informant with evidence (without naming Ted outright), he might discreetly keep an eye out. But then he’d likely try to nab Ted.

No, that could betray Ted’s trust. And Park’s newfound alliance with him is tentative—if Ted gets spooked by any police presence, it might unravel.

I decide to compromise by texting Park that I’m meeting “the client” tonight again to follow a lead he claims to have. I assure you I’ll be careful and keep it short. I half expect a call immediately telling me not to go. But after five minutes, Park replies: Alright. Be careful. Keep the location public and leave if anything feels off. Call me after.

It’s a relief that he didn’t forbid it; it shows he’s trying to trust me as I am him.

I spend the rest of the afternoon nervously cleaning the already tidy house and going over in my mind all the threads connecting the Mitchells, Bridgette, and Ted. Each time I pass by the window, I check for any unusual cars on the road. None that I can tell.

By 7:30, twilight is descending. I change into jeans, flats, and a light jacket with a hood—something inconspicuous. After a moment’s thought, I slip the small GPS tracker into my pocket. Could it come in handy? Not sure, but I feel better having it.

The park is only a short drive away. I arrive just before 8 and park on a side street. The area is quiet, the fountain at the center of Centennial Park lit softly by lampposts. The benches where we met earlier are mostly empty now, save for a couple walking a dog on the far side and a lone man in a baseball cap reading a newspaper by the fountain.

I make a slow circuit of the walking path, scanning for Ted. A jogger passes, then a pair of teenage girls. I don’t spot him. Could he be late or hiding? My senses prickle. This reminds me of a spy novel rendezvous. I half expect someone to whisper a code phrase.

“Evening, Doc,” says a low voice behind me. I whirl, hand at my throat. A wiry man in a hoodie and baseball cap stands a few feet away. For a split second, I don’t recognize him—his beard is gone, and with it the scruffy, rugged look. Instead, he’s clean-shaven, looking younger, almost boyish. But those hazel eyes gleam familiarly under the cap.

“Ted,” I exhale, relief and surprise mingling. “Good disguise. I didn’t know you without the beard.”

He gives a half-smile and pulls the cap brim lower. “Felt like a liability. I needed a new face. Sorry if I startled you.”

I step closer. “No, it’s fine. I’m just glad you’re safe.” We share a brief, warm look. Then I remember why we’re here. “You said you have something?”

He nods and gestures for me to follow him off the main path, toward a stand of magnolia trees just beyond a lamppost’s glow. My heart thumps; I scan around. We’re semi-secluded but still visible enough if anyone were watching. It should be okay.

From inside his hoodie, Ted produces a folded paper. He hands it to me, and I realize it’s a printed photograph. In the dim light, I make out a blurry but telling scene: a black SUV at night, parked on what looks like a residential street. The timestamp on the image reads “05/08 12:06”. Yesterday, just after noon.

My eyes widen. The black SUV has a very distinctive chrome grille. “Is this—?”

“Derek Mitchell’s car,” Ted confirms, voice low and triumphant. “A friend of mine works security cameras for a complex near Bridgette’s building. We pulled this from a traffic cam down the block. It shows Derek’s SUV driving toward her place around noon on May 8. There’s another clip of it speeding away less than twenty minutes later.”

I stare at the photo. It’s grainy, but you can clearly see a man in the driver’s seat through the windshield—hard to identify at this distance, but the build and timing match Derek. My heart pounds. This is evidence. Real evidence. “Ted... this is huge.”

His eyes blaze. “Damn right it is. Puts that bastard right there when Bridgette was killed. And it explains why the timeline changed—they thought she died later, maybe after I visited her that evening, but this shows it happened midday. Derek must’ve caught her by surprise.” His jaw is tight; I can see how much it’s taking him not to explode in rage.

I touch his arm lightly. “This is enough to get the police to question him at least, maybe search his car or residence.”

Ted snorts. “If they actually want to. But with the Mitchells’ reach? Who knows. I wanted you to see it first—figure out the best way to use it.”

He trusts me with this critical piece. I feel a surge of responsibility. “Park should see this too. He’s in trial tomorrow and planning to implicate Derek for Marjorie’s murder. This evidence ties Derek to Bridgette’s.”

Ted’s expression flickers with something like respect. “Your husband came around on Derek?”

“He found out Derek was likely in town when Marjorie—Aaron’s wife—was killed. He’s already got dirt on him. Now this… it basically confirms Derek as a murderer twice over.”

Ted exhales, looking up at the darkening sky through the tree branches. “Justice,” he mutters, like he’s savoring the word but afraid to taste it fully. “If they actually nail him, Caroline… that means my sister—” He breaks off, voice choked.

Impulsively, I step forward and wrap my arms around him. It’s not a romantic hug, just a human one, offering comfort and sharing the weight. After a beat, he returns the embrace tightly, trembling. “She’ll get justice,” I whisper. “I promise.”

He nods against my shoulder and then gently pulls back, clearing his throat. His eyes shine with unshed tears, making them luminous in the low light. “Sorry. I—”

“No, don’t apologize,” I say firmly. “You’re allowed to feel this.”

He smiles sadly. “Not used to it, I guess. Thank you.”

We lapse into a charged silence. He’s standing close, the heat of emotion between us. I recall Park’s worried words about me drifting into someone else’s arms. But this moment with Ted—it isn’t about romance or lust. It’s about shared pain and purpose. Perhaps once I might have found myself infatuated with this intense, wounded man. But now, I just feel camaraderie and protectiveness. He’s become dear to me, but not in the way Park is.

I step back, refocusing. “We need to plan how to present this. I think you should allow me to share it with Park and Detective Anderson. They’ll jump on it.”

Ted looks wary but nods. “If you trust them. I trust you.”

I reach into my jacket pocket. “We should also consider something Park’s PI dug up: Derek’s likely responsible for his stepmom’s murder too. If the cops realize the same person might have done both, they’ll have double incentive to act. And one more thing—” I pull out the mini tracker, holding it up between us. “This is a tracker you dropped. I kept it. Could we… maybe use it? If Derek’s still free, maybe track him?”

Ted blinks, then lets out a low chuckle. “I did drop that, didn’t I? Wasn’t intentional, but good that you have it.” He thinks for a moment. “If you or Park can slip that onto his vehicle somehow, that’d be gold. But careful—if he finds it, that tips him off.”

“True.” Perhaps a job for Park’s PI or someone stealthy. I tuck it away again. “We’ll figure something.”

Ted glances around us, then at his watch. “We should split up. I don’t want to linger too long.”

I nod, suddenly realizing how tense my shoulders have been this entire meeting. “Okay.” I clutch the photo carefully. “I’ll call Park on my way home, show him this. And we’ll go to Matthew first thing.”

Ted hesitates, then reaches out and gently squeezes my hand. “Be careful. Mitchells don’t play nice. And… thank you, Caroline. I wouldn’t have gotten this far without you.”

Warmth blooms in my chest. “Likewise. Hang in there just a bit longer. By tomorrow, the tide will turn.”

He releases my hand and offers a small smile. “Till tomorrow, then.” With a last searching look, he turns and strides off, vanishing into the shadows beyond the fountain. A ghost indeed.

I let out a breath I didn’t realize I’d been holding. That photo in my grasp feels like a burning coal—dangerous but illuminating. We finally have proof. A rush of exhilaration passes through me, followed by a shiver of paranoia. I swiftly walk back to my car, scanning for any sign I was being watched. Nothing obvious, just the couple with the dog now exiting the park, the lamplights flickering on.

Once safely in my locked car, I pull out my phone to call Park. He answers on the second ring. “Caroline? You okay?” He sounds anxious.

“I’m fine,” I assure. “And I have something. Something big.”

I hear him inhale sharply as I explain about the traffic cam photo of Derek’s SUV near Bridgette’s place. “I have it in hand. Ted got it through a friend.”

“Holy—Caroline, that’s… If it’s legit, that blows this wide open.” He’s already in lawyer-strategy mode. “We need to get that to the police anonymously, or present it at trial somehow—though trial is for Marjorie’s murder, not Bridgette’s. But if Derek is outed as her killer, it casts doubt on him in Marjorie’s case too.”

“We’ll figure out the channel. I thought Matthew might be best—he’d trust where it came from if we say a concerned citizen forwarded it or something.”

“Yes, that could work.” Park’s voice is alive with energy. “God, Caro, you actually did it. You and Ted.”

“You’re not mad?” I venture softly.

He lets out a strained chuckle. “Mad? I’m stunned. And grateful. And—well, irritated that he managed to upstage my PI in two days, but I’ll let that slide.” There’s pride in his tone, too, for me. It warms me through.

“Come home,” he adds gently. “It’s late. We’ll go see Matthew first thing in the morning with that evidence. I want you off the streets now, okay? We’re too close to risk anything happening tonight.”

I agree. “On my way. See you soon.”

Driving back, I can’t wipe the grin off my face. Not only did we get something concrete, but Park’s acceptance and relief are palpable. For the first time in a long time, I feel like we’re completely in sync.

As I pull into our driveway, headlights sweep across the front of the house. It looks peaceful, unchanged—belying the tempest of the past days. I hurry inside. Park practically meets me at the door. Before any words, he envelops me in a tight hug. I melt into it.

“You’re amazing,” he murmurs into my hair. “And infuriating. But mostly amazing.”

I laugh softly against his chest. “I’ll take that.”

We move to the living room, and I show him the printed photo. He studies it closely under a lamp, jaw set in righteous fury. “That’s him. It’s got to be.”

We discuss the plan. Park will call Matthew early, framing this as a tip that came through his PI’s network to avoid exposing Ted. Matthew will want Ted off the hook as much as anyone once he sees Derek front and center. If all goes well, Derek Mitchell will be in custody by midday, charged with Bridgette’s murder—maybe even Marjorie’s once they press him.

And our part in this? Possibly quietly glossed over. I don’t mind that. I’d rather not be publicly entangled in this bizarre triangle any more than I already am.

Later in bed, Park and I lie facing each other in the dark. The events replay in our whispered conversation—both of us a little in awe of how the pieces fell into place. There’s sadness too; justice coming means acknowledging the tragedy of Bridgette’s fate and Marjorie’s. Park admits softly that he feels guilty for Bridgette being in harm’s way. I soothe him by pointing out that he couldn’t have known any of this would happen. If anything, what happened to her—what happened to all of us—was set in motion by the Mitchells’ secrets and choices, not his moment of weakness alone.

He holds me a little tighter after that. “How did I ever deserve you?” he whispers.

I don’t respond with words. I just kiss him, slowly and tenderly, pouring all the complicated forgiveness and love I still harbor into that embrace. He returns it, and for the first night in a long time, we fall asleep holding each other close, no walls between us.

Tomorrow will bring new battles—courtroom fireworks, revelations that could shake Charleston’s elite. But tonight, in this fragile calm, I allow myself hope. Hope that the truth will prevail. Hope that those truly guilty will answer for their sins. And hope that Park and I, having walked through fire, can emerge together, stronger than before.`
