      content: `Caroline,  Wednesday, May 10, Charleston High Court, Charleston (Midday)


The moment Judge Warwick announces the lunch recess, a susurration of chatter fills the courtroom. I release a breath I hadn’t realized I was holding. My heart has been in my throat all morning, but I kept my face composed—impassive, calm, every inch the dignified wife standing by her husband. I’ve had practice at this; yesterday at the bail hearing, I did the same, schooling my features into serenity even as gossiping “friends” stared at me with pity.. Today, I refuse to give anyone the satisfaction of seeing me rattled.

But it was hard. God, was it hard. Sitting there a few yards behind Park, I felt every blow of the prosecution’s words. Hearing Jerry Sullivan describe Marjorie Mitchell’s skull being shattered and broken bones from repeated strikes made my stomach twist in revulsion. Images flashed in my mind unbidden—Marjorie’s imagined terror, Bridgette’s likely last moments. I had to clasp my hands in my lap to hide their trembling when the medical examiner detailed the brutality.. Only by focusing on Park’s steady voice during his cross-examinations did I keep myself grounded. He would glance my way every so often, almost as if checking on me, and I’d give him the smallest of resolute nods. I’m okay, I’ll go back to him. Keep going.

And oh, did he keep going. My chest swelled with pride watching him systematically dismantle the State’s case piece by piece. When Park boldly suggested that someone else, Derek, might have been the real threat to Marjorie, I nearly wanted to jump up and cheer. Instead, I maintained my poised exterior, but inside I was elated. I saw Richard Mitchell’s face go pale at the mention of his son’s name, and I felt a fierce satisfaction. That’s right, I thought. The truth is coming for you all.

Now, as spectators mill about and jurors file out for their break, I stand and smooth my skirt. A few people glance at me, some curious, others sympathetic. I ignore them. Let them look. After the sensational revelations Park made, I suspect I’m not just “the scorned wife” in their eyes anymore, but part of the team exposing a scandal. If only they knew the half of it.

I spot Park near the defense table, conferring with Kidman and packing away some files. He catches my eye and gives me a tiny, reassuring smile. I return it with one of my own. We’re winnin',g I can feel it. There’s a lightness to Park’s expression I haven’t seen in ages. He looks energized, determined.

I want nothing more than to go to him, to whisper how amazing he’s doing and perhaps steal a quick embrace. But a throng of reporters has already pressed forward at the edges of the bar, and court security is ushering them back. I should keep my distance for now and let Park work. We’ll have our moment later.

I slip out the side door of the gallery into the hallway, the clack of my low heels mixing with the echo of voices in the marble corridor. The air outside the courtroom is cooler, and I realize I’m perspiring lightly, partly from nerves, partly from Charleston’s creeping humidity even indoors. I take a deep breath, steadying myself against a surge of emotions. It’s happening. Derek will be exposed, perhaps even arrested, before the day is done, and Bridgette…Bridgette will get some measure of justice.

Bridgette. The name brings a swirl of complicated feelings. Sadness, anger, even a touch of belated sympathy. I’ll never like what she did with Park, but she didn’t deserve to be murdered over whatever she discovered. No one does. If Derek Mitchell truly killed his stepmother and then Bridgette tohide it, he’s a monster hiding behind the Mitchell family’s prestige. And that monster is about to face the light.

The hallway is lined with familiar faces from Charleston society who came to watch the trial, like it’s some matinee entertainment. I notice Lily Thomson in a chic beige ensemble, chatting in low tones with another woman. The moment Lily sees me, she waves. I consider pretending I didn’t notice, but she’s already bustling over, her heels clicking.

“Caroline!” Lily’s voice drips with a saccharine mix of concern and excitement. “My goodness, what a morning, hmm? How are you holding up, dear?”

I muster a cordial smile. Lily was one of those whispering about me at the bail hearing, and I haven’t forgotten. But I maintain civility. “I’m alright, Lily. It’s certainly been…eventful.”

She presses a manicured hand to her chest, leaning in as if confiding. “I just want you to know, we’re all so impressed by how strong you’ve been through all this.” Her eyes flick past me, likely hoping to spot Park. “And Park, goodness. His performance today! None of us expected that twist. Derek Mitchell! Who would have imagined?”

I catch a slight undertone in her voice; she’s fishing for any insider info. Gossip runs deep in Charleston’s elite, and Lily thrives on it. I give her nothing. “Justice can take surprising turns,” I reply mildly. “If you’ll excuse me, I need to make a call.”

“Oh! Of course, of course,” Lily backpedals with an apologetic smile. “We’ll catch up later?”

“Maybe,” I say noncommittally, already stepping away. I have neither the time nor the patience to play social butterfly right now.

I head toward a quieter alcove near the courthouse’s side exit, ironically, the same spot where Ted first approached me after the bail hearing.. Thinking of that day, and how far things have spiraled since, I shake my head in amazement. Less than 48 hours ago, I barely knew Ted Leah; now, his quest and mine are deeply intertwined. And Park and I… we were on opposite sides of an emotional canyon just yesterday. Now we’re closer than we’ve been in months, united by purpose and honesty. Life changes on a dime.

As if summoned by thought, I see Detective Matthew Anderson stride through the side entrance, scanning the hallway. When his eyes land on me, he gives a quick nod and approaches. My pulse picks up; he must have news.

“Matthew,” I greet, keeping my voice down. “Hi.”

“Hi, Caroline.” He offers a gentle smile—one I recognize as genuine concern. He’s known us long enough to treat me like a friend first, witness second.. “How are you holding up?”

“I’m alright,” I say, appreciating that he actually wants the truth, not a polite platitude. “Better now, I think. It’s been… intense in there.”

He nods. “Your husband is doing a hell of a job.” Then his expression turns a touch sly. “He might’ve had a little outside help with that bold strategy, hmm?”

I huff a soft laugh, not denying it. Matthew knows me too well to think I’ve been idle. “Maybe a nudge or two.”

His face grows more serious. “Listen, I have an update, and I figured you’d want to know right away.” He lowers his voice. “We picked up Derek Mitchell about ten minutes ago.”

My breath catches. Even expecting it, hearing the words floods me with relief. “So it’s done?”

“It’s done,” he confirms. “He’s being processed and will be... available for testimony, let’s say, this afternoon.”

I let out a shuddering exhale. My eyes sting suddenly, to my surprise. I blink against the threat of tears. Bridgette’s killer—if Derek truly is—off the streets. “Thank you,” I whisper. “Truly, Matthew. For everything.”

He raises a hand modestly. “Just doing my job. You and Park handed us the key, really.” He pauses, then adds carefully, “We’ll ensure Theodore Leah is cleared in our system as well. Given the evidence, I doubt he’ll even need to come in for more than a brief statement. He’s effectively off the hook.”

A weight I didn’t fully realize I was carrying slides off my shoulders. Ted will be safe, and the suspicion hanging over him will be gone.. “That’s wonderful news,” I say, heartfelt.

Matthew hesitates, then ventures, “Have you been in touch with him?”

I glance around to ensure no eavesdroppers, then nod. “We’ve… kept in contact. I should let him know Derek’s in custody. He’s been so afraid.”

Matthew pats my arm gently. “Go ahead. Trial resumes in half an hour. Make your calls. And Caroline,” he adds, lowering his head to catch my gaze, “you did good. This whole thing… it could have gone differently if you hadn’t stepped in when you did.”

Warmth blooms in my chest. Coming from a seasoned detective like him, that means something. “I couldn’t sit by,” I murmur. “Not when I realized what was really going on.”

He smiles. “Well, you’re a braver woman than most. Go on now, I’ve got to brief the judge and get a certain someone ready to testify.” The twinkle in his eye as he says that gives away his satisfaction.

I nod and watch as Matthew heads off briskly towards the judge’s chambers. My heart is thumping, a mixture of triumph and anticipation. Derek Mitchell is caught. Park will be calling him to the stand within the hour. Oh, to be a fly on the wall when that happens…

Focus, Caroline. I reach into my purse for my phone and step into the alcove’s shadow for a bit of privacy. There are a few new messages, one from my mother (undoubtedly having caught wind of the trial drama; I’ll deal with that later), and one from an unknown number that I realize is likely a reporter. Delete. I open the text thread with Ted.

My fingers tremble slightly as I type: They caught Derek. He’s in custody now. Park plans to confront him in court after lunch. I hit send and add another quick line: You should be safe. Matthew says you’ll be cleared fully soon.

The reply comes almost instantaneously: Holy shit. Thank you for telling me. I owe both of you so much. I can practically feel the palpable relief behind his words. I picture Ted wherever he’s holed up, reading this and maybe sinking into a chair, the weight of fear finally lifting.

He sends another message: Should I come down there?

I bite my lip, considering. Part of me thinks he deserves to see the moment Derek is exposed, but it’s risky. Better not get too close yet. We’ll update you after. Stay low just a little longer.

His response is simple: Understood. And… thank Park for me. For believing.

I smile at the phone. This, coming from Ted who distrusted Park so deeply mere days ago, is huge. I will, I type back. Hang tight. Almost over. I add a small thumbs-up emoji, feeling slightly absurd but wanting to keep his spirits up. He hears the message in response.

I tuck my phone away and lean against the cool wall for a moment, closing my eyes. It’s almost over. We’re so close. A gentle breath shudders out of me, and I allow myself a moment to feel it—the catharsis of having done something truly meaningful. Bridgette, I think silently, I don’t know if somehow you can know this, but we did right by you. We’re going to make sure the man who did this faces justice.

With a start, I realize the lunch break is nearly over. The corridor has thinned as people filter back toward the courtroom. I smooth my blouse, straighten my posture, and make my way back.

Inside Courtroom 2B, the atmosphere feels electrically charged. News travels fast—half of Charleston likely knows by now that Park implicated Derek Mitchell. There’s an excited tension among the spectators. I hear snippets as I pass: “...arrested during lunch, I heard…” and “Mitchell’s son, can you imagine, what a scandal…”

I resume my seat in the gallery, heart beginning to hammer in anticipation. Park is already at the defense table, reviewing notes with Kidman. He hasn’t seen me yet. Across the way at the prosecution table, Jerry Sullivan stands rigid, arms crossed, in a quiet but heated conversation with a tall, sandy-haired man in a tailored suit—who I belatedly recognize as Franklin Mitchell, Derek’s older brother. Franklin’s face is flushed, and even from here I can tell he’s rattled. It strikes me: the prosecution must have gotten word that their star defense attorney foe just turned this trial upside down. Franklin likely barreled down here to do damage control for the family.

Richard Mitchell is nowhere to be seen—perhaps his health or nerves gave out, or he’s conferring with lawyers outside. Either way, the Mitchell family presence is in disarray. A pang of something—pity?—hits me when I see Franklin rubbing his forehead with a trembling hand. In a matter of hours, the facade of their powerful clan has crumbled. But then I think of Marjorie, of Bridgette, and my sympathy hardens. This is on them. If they’d let the truth come out to begin with, how many lives would have been spared ruin?

The bailiff’s voice calls out: “All rise.” Judge Warwick enters once more, giving us all a curt nod as we retake our seats.

I quickly glance over my shoulder, and my breath catches. Two uniformed deputies have entered behind the judge—and between them, wearing an ill-fitting suit jacket over what looks like a hastily changed prison shirt, is Derek Mitchell. Even without the obvious custody, I guess who he is in an instant. The resemblance to Aaron is there: tall and broad-shouldered, the same sharp nose and strong jawline as his father. But Derek’s eyes—there’s a wildness to them, a frantic energy barely leashed. He looks around the courtroom as if seeking an escape route, then composes his face into a cocky smirk.

An angry purple bruise mars Derek’s left cheekbone. I wonder if he resisted arrest. He looks both defiant and panicked—an odd mix that sends a chill through me. This man murdered his stepmother in cold blood, if our suspicions are right. This man killed Bridgette. My fingers dig into my purse on my lap, knuckles whitening. I remind myself to breathe.

Beside me, others in the gallery have noticed the deputies and Dere, too. A ripple of murmurs surges like a wave: “That’s him,” “Is that the son?” “He’s in handcuffs!” The judge hasn’t called the court to order yet, and the noise grows.

Judge Warwick raps her gavel sharply. “Order! This courtroom will come to order or I will clear it.” The murmuring subsides to an awed hush. She eyes the deputies with their charge and then looks to Jerry Sullivan. “Mr. Sullivan, I wasn’t aware the State intended to call a new witness this afternoon. And one in custody, no less.” Her tone is dry, letting him know she’s not pleased to be blindsided.

Jerry clears his throat. I can see the frustration rolling off him—this is far from how he envisioned his trial going. “Your Honor, the individual in question is actually being called by the defense.”

Warwick’s eyebrow cocks, and she turns to Park. “Mr. Limond, care to explain?”

Park stands, buttoning his suit jacket, and I notice he sends a glance back toward me and the gallery. His gaze finds mine. In it, I see resolve, fire, even a hint of triumph. I give him the slightest nod of encouragement. Go get him.

“Your Honor,” Park says in a controlled tone, “this is Derek Mitchell. He is indeed our next witness.” He casts a measured look at Derek, who meets his eyes with a glare. “It seems Mr. Mitchell’s availability was ensured during the recess by law enforcement.”

A few titters break out at Park’s diplomatic phrasing. The judge’s mouth twitches as if fighting a grim smile. “Very well. If there are no objections…?”

Jerry nearly sputters. “We— the State, that is— have no objection to Mr. Derek Mitchell testifying, Your Honor.” I suspect Jerry doesn’t dare object; it would look like he’s hiding something from the jury. Smartly, he sits, though there’s a visible clench in his jaw.

The bailiff escorts Derek to the witness stand. The handcuffs are removed, but a deputy stays posted nearby. Derek straightens his rumpled jacket and smooths his dark hair, attempting nonchalance. But from my vantage, I see how his hand trembles when he raises it to take the oath.

“Do you swear or affirm that the testimony you shall give in the matter now pending before this court shall be the truth, the whole truth, and nothing but the truth, so help you God?” the clerk recites.

Derek’s voice is lower than I expected, with a slight quiver he tries to mask as bravado. “Yeah. I do,” he says.

As he sits, I notice him shifting, shoulders squared aggressively. His eyes flick out to the gallery. For one brief moment, they land on me. I don’t look away. What he sees on my face, I can’t be sure—maybe the sum of all the lives he’s upended glaring back at him. His lip curls faintly before he turns his focus to Park.

I inhale slowly. This is it—the moment we’ve been racing toward. Park approaches the witness stand, every inch the poised litigator. From the defense table, Kidman watches with barely restrained excitement. Jerry leans forward, bracing for the unknown. The jurors’ eyes are wide, riveted by the drama of a son of the defendant being dramatically hauled in to testify.

And me? I fold my hands tightly in my lap and hold Park in my sight. He’s got this—I know it in my bones. And whatever happens next, we’ll face it together.`
