      title: 'Chapter Seventeen',
      content: `Park,  Tuesday, June 20, Limond Residence, Charleston (Evening)


Freedom tastes like rosemary chicken and relief. At least, it should. Caroline went all-out, cooking a celebratory dinner tonight. Our dining room table is set with our best plates, candles flickering, a basket of fresh buttery rolls, and a bottle of our favorite red breathing. It’s an intimate feast meant for two, and it smells amazing. Yet I can barely swallow a bite.

I push a piece of chicken around in the sauce, my appetite lost to the turmoil still churning in me. Across the table, Caroline watches quietly. The soft golden light makes her hair shine, her beautiful face drawn in concern. I don’t deserve the tenderness in her eyes, not after everything I’ve put her through.

“Caroline…” I rasp, breaking the silence. My throat feels thick. “I don’t deserve you.”

Her brows knit. “Park—”

I shake my head and set down my fork with a clatter. Emotion wells up hard and fast, almost choking me. “No, let me say this. Please.” I meet her gaze, my vision blurring. “I disgraced you. I lied to you. I betrayed our marriage, and I dragged your name through the mud with mine. Yet there you were, day after day in that courtroom, standing by me. Defending me even when I didn’t deserve defense.” My voice cracks, and tears I thought I’d run dry threaten anew. “I’m so sorry, Caroline. For all of it. I will spend the rest of my life making this right, if… if you’ll let me.”

By the time I finish, my cheeks are wet. Caroline’s lips surprise part. She wasn’t expecting an outpouring, maybe. I wasn’t either, but I can’t hold it back. She needs to know. Hell, I need her to know—she is everything. Not Bridgette, not anyone else.

Caroline’s eyes glisten. She pushes her chair back and comes around to my side. Before I can rise, she kneels next to me and takes my hand. The gesture floors me—my proud wife on her knees by my chair. I quickly tug her up to sit on my lap instead, wrapping my arms around her waist. She lets me, resting a hand on my cheek.

“I also owe you an apology,” she says softly.

I blink, confused. “For what? You did nothing wrong.”

Caroline draws a shaky breath. “Park… I lost the baby.”

Her words take a moment to penetrate. When they do, my heart stops. “What?” I whisper.

She bites her trembling lip. “The stress, the nightmare of these weeks—it was too much. I miscarried early on. Right before your arraignment.” Her eyes brim over. “I’m sorry. I was just so overwhelmed. I—I didn’t even tell you I was pregnant in a proper way, I blurted it out to hurt someone else. And then… I lost it.”

“Oh, Caroline.” I pull her into a fierce embrace as she breaks down in sobs against my shoulder. Pain lances through me, sharp and deep. A child… we were going to have a baby? I’d dreamed of that for so long, and in the chaos, I barely had time to be happy about it. Now the dream’s gone. And she went through that agony alone, because I was locked up.

“This isn’t your fault,” I murmur into her hair, rocking her gently. My own tears fall into her silky strands. “Don’t you dare think that. We’ll… we’ll try again, okay? When we’re ready. This isn’t the end for us, I promise.” My voice is fierce through the tears. I realize I’m trying to convince myself, too. The idea of another chance, another baby, is a beacon I desperately need right now.

She nods against me, sniffing. “Okay.”

I tilt her chin up and kiss her—softly, lingeringly. It’s the first real kiss we’ve shared in… God, I don’t even know how long. It tastes of salt from our tears and carries years of regret and longing. She responds with equal fervor, fingers curling into my shirt.

Within moments, the need to reconnect overwhelms everything else. I stand, lifting her with me. She wraps her legs around my waist instinctively. Our dinner remains half-eaten on the table, candles burning down, but we don’t care.

I carry her to the bedroom, kissing her deeply all the while. We shed clothes in a desperate haze. This isn’t the frenzied, rough coupling from when things first fell apart. This is slow, tender—almost reverent. I memorize every inch of her skin with my hands, my lips, silently apologizing with every caress. She arches under me, whispering my name like a benediction.

When we finally come together, it’s healing and raw. I bury my face in her neck as waves of pleasure and anguish roll through us in equal measure. Her nails bite my back, holding me to her as if she can’t bear to let go.

After, we lie tangled in sheets damp with sweat and tears. Caroline’s head rests on my chest, her fingers tracing idle patterns over my heart. I stroke her hair, staring at the ceiling, feeling more at peace than I have in ages. Exhaustion is pulling me under, but I fight it to savor this fragile truce between us.

I press a kiss to her forehead. “I love you,” I murmur into the darkness, voice thick with emotion.

She nestles closer. “Love you too,” she whispers. And I believe she means it—in this moment at least.

For a while, we just listen to each other breathe. I think she’s fallen asleep when she suddenly speaks, her voice very small: “Park… the Mitchell brothers. Why do you think they came to the courthouse?”

I stiffen slightly, the question pricking at the very edge of my conscience where I’d tried to ignore it. Truth is, since seeing them today, I haven’t stopped wondering. “I’m not sure,” I admit. “Maybe to gloat. Maybe to remind me they’re still out there.”

She lifts her head, looking at me with troubled eyes. “Do you think they really did it? Killed her?”

In the dark, I can only see the outline of Caroline’s face, but I hear the unease. I sigh. “I don’t know. They had motive. And they’re certainly capable of that level of cruelty. But something about it still doesn’t sit right.”

She’s quiet for a moment, then lies back down, hugging me tighter as if to ward off a chill. “Let’s not borrow more trouble,” she whispers. “We have our lives back. I don’t want to waste this second chance by chasing ghosts.”

I rub her back soothingly, though my mind churns. Chasing ghosts… Is that what pursuing Bridgette’s killer would be? A fool’s errand that could ruin us all over again?

Caroline is right in a sense. We’ve paid enough. She’s suffered enough. Maybe letting the authorities handle it—if they even plan to—is the smart choice.

“Okay,” I murmur, for her sake. “No more looking back. Only forward.”

She relaxes a little, and soon her breathing deepens, sleep claiming her. I remain awake a while longer, staring into the shadows, thoughts drifting to Bridgette’s smile, Bridgette’s laugh. The promises I made her that I never intended to keep. The image of her lifeless eyes in that bathtub flashes behind my eyelids, and I flinch.

I owe her justice, an inner voice insists. But my wife’s sleeping form in my arms is a heavier argument: I owe Caroline peace I nearly lost her forever, both to my own mistakes and to this nightmare. If diving back into it would risk our hard-won reconciliation, can I justify that?

I kiss the top of Caroline’s head and close my eyes. For now, I choose her. I choose us.

Maybe that makes me a coward. Or maybe it makes me a man who finally knows what truly matters.

In the darkness, I silently promise: No more secrets, no more lies. Caroline and I will rebuild from here, brick by brick.

And if the truth about Bridgette comes knocking one day… I’ll deal with it then.`
