      content: `Caroline,  Thursday, June 22, Limond Residence, Charleston (Morning)


I wake to sunlight filtering through the curtains and the scent of fresh coffee. For one blissful moment, I feel normal. Better than normal—light. Like the heaviness of the past months has finally lifted.

Then I notice Park isn’t in bed. I stretch, sore in many pleasant places from our long night of reconciliation, and slip on a silk robe. Padding out to the living room, I hear low voices.

Park is seated on the edge of the sofa, fully dressed in jeans and a polo. Detective Matthew Anderson sits across from him, elbows on his knees. Both men look grave. They stop talking when I appear.

“Good morning,” I say softly, cinching my robe tie. “I didn’t realize we had company.”

“Sorry,” Park says, offering a faint smile. “You were sleeping so soundly, I didn’t want to wake you. Matthew dropped by a few minutes ago.”

Matthew stands politely. “Caroline.” He gives me a nod of greeting, though his expression remains tense.

I settle into the armchair adjacent, pulling my robe tighter around me. “Let me guess—shop talk?” I try to sound light, but my stomach flutters with dread. The last thing I want is Matthew dragging Park back into the darkness.

Park glances at Matthew, who clears his throat. “I was just updating Park on the official investigation into Bridgette’s murder,” Matthew says. “Off the record, of course.”

“Official investigation,” I echo. “You mean the one that doesn’t involve Park now.”

Matthew’s lips quirk. “Right. Now that he’s not the target, the DA’s office is—grudgingly—redirecting. But I’ll be honest: without Park, they have nothing solid. Jerry’s team is dragging their feet.”

I cluck my tongue. Typical. Jerry would rather drop it than admit the Mitchells or someone else might have fooled him.

Park runs a hand over his face. “So you’re saying whoever did this might get away with it because Jerry can’t swallow his pride?”

Matthew nods grimly. “Unless new evidence falls into their lap, yeah. They consider it an unsolved homicide with no leads. They’re more interested in salvaging Jerry’s reputation after losing your case.”

A silence falls. Park’s jaw tenses. I can practically see the war inside him reigniting—the part that yearns for truth versus the part that just wants to move on.

I step in before he can respond. “Matthew, I appreciate you informing us. But if the authorities aren’t pursuing it, perhaps that’s for the best.”

Both men look at me in surprise. I fold my hands calmly. “We’ve all been through hell. Maybe it’s time to let this go. Dwelling on Bridgette’s case will only prolong everyone’s pain.”

Matthew raises a brow. “Justice left undone doesn’t sit right with me, Caroline. I know it doesn’t sit right with Park, either.”

I force a gentle smile. “What good is justice if it destroys the living in the process? Park has a second chance now—to rebuild his life, our life. I don’t want anything jeopardizing that.”

Park frowns, shifting uncomfortably. “Caro, we talked about this. If the Mitchells—”

I reach over and put a hand on his. “And we agreed to move forward, didn’t we? Let the law handle the Mitchells.” I turn to Matthew. “The police can keep investigating quietly, right? Without involving Park.”

Matthew looks between us, sensing the marital undercurrents. He sighs. “Sure. We can keep digging on our end. I just… thought Park might have insights or, I don’t know, want to help.”

Park opens his mouth, but I squeeze his hand hard. He glances at me, conflicted. I raise my eyebrows in a subtle plea. Let it go.

“Actually,” Park says slowly, “Caroline’s right. I have to think about my family now. Getting entangled again… it could backfire.” He turns to Matthew, voice steadier. “I’m sorry, Matt. I can’t be a part of it. Not this time.”

Disappointment flickers over Matthew’s face, but he nods. “Understood. I don’t agree, but I understand.” He stands. “If either of you hears or remembers anything that might help, let me know, okay?”

“Of course,” I say warmly, standing as well. “Thank you for everything, Matthew. Truly.”

He gives a small, weary smile. “Take care of each other.” With that, he sees himself out.

The door barely clicks shut before Park pulls his hand from mine and stalks a few paces away, raking a hand through his hair. “Caroline—” he begins, an edge in his voice.

I steel myself. “I know you’re upset.”

He swings around to face me. “Upset? I’m—” He struggles for words. “A woman is dead. Because she got involved with me. And the bastards who likely did it are walking free.” He lowers his voice, anger and guilt simmering. “How can I live with that?”

I step forward. “The same way I’m living with the fact that my husband slept with that woman and lied about it.”

He flinches. I rarely speak of it so bluntly. “That’s… different,” he mutters.

“Is it? Both truths hurt, Park. But we choose what to do with them now.” I cup his cheek, making him look at me. “I choose to let the past be past. I want to move on. I want us to move on.” My eyes search his. “Please, Park. Choose us, not her ghost.”

His posture slackens, resolve wavering. “It’s not about her ghost… it’s about doing what’s right.”

I soften my tone, sliding my arms around his waist. “Sometimes doing what’s right for the ones you love has to come before abstract justice. We nearly lost each other. I can’t go back to that dark place. I won’t.” My voice quivers despite myself. “Does she mean that much to you? That you’d risk everything to avenge her?”

Park’s eyes widen. “No—God, no.” He enfolds me in his arms. “You’re what matters. You and our future. I’m not going to risk that.”

I breathe out slowly in relief, burying my face against his chest. “Thank you,” I whisper. Inside, a triumphant warmth unfurls. He’s letting it go. We can be free. I can be free.

He presses a kiss to the top of my head. “I’m sorry. I just needed to hear it out loud. To be sure.”

I nod, pulling back to meet his gaze. “Matthew will keep digging safely, I’m sure. And if anything solid turns up, the police can act. We don’t need to be involved.”

Park takes a deep breath, then nods. “Alright.” He kisses my forehead. “No more looking back.”

A genuine smile curves my lips. To seal the promise, I rise on tiptoe and kiss him—a slow, grateful kiss. He responds with equal tenderness, hands resting on my hips. When we part, I whisper, “No more mention of… her. Or any of it. Clean slate.”

He manages a tiny smile. “Deal.”

As if to punctuate it, I untie my robe and let it slide off, pooling silk at my feet. Park’s breath catches. I take his hand and guide it to the curve of my waist. “Bedroom?” I suggest softly.

A flicker of heat and something like relief crosses his face. “Bedroom,” he agrees hoarsely.

We hardly make it to the bed before we’re tangled together, shedding the last barriers between us. This time our lovemaking has an almost frantic edge—like we’re both determined to blot out the past with sheer physical closeness. Park moves above me with urgency; I meet him with equal fervor. Our moans echo in the sunlit room as we reaffirm and reclaim what’s ours.

After, he falls asleep in exhaustion, arms wrapped around me protectively. But I stay awake, staring at the ceiling, adrenaline still thrumming through my veins.

He chose me. Over her. Over justice for her. A slow smile spreads on my lips as I watch him sleeping, so trusting and spent.

Bridgette Leah is truly gone now—from our lives, from his mind. He’s never going to pursue it. Which means I’m safe. We’re safe.

My eyes drift to the window where a light rain has begun pattering. The soft rhythm soothes me as I consider the future—one where this dark chapter is fully behind us.

I curl closer to Park, resting my head on his chest. His heartbeat is steady, strong. Mine echoes it in contentment.

Somewhere deep down, a small voice asks if I feel any guilt. But it’s lost in the reassuring cadence of his breathing. I only feel an overwhelming sense of victory—and relief.

We survived. Our marriage survived. Sometimes, to save what you love, lines must be crossed. I’d do it all again if I had to.

I close my eyes, letting the rain wash the last remnants of worry from my mind. Bridgette Leah’s name will never be spoken in this house again. That chapter is closed.

Outside, thunder rumbles lightly. I smile in the darkness and tighten my arm around my husband, finally at peace with the choices I’ve made.`
